e [[DVD]], three [[Single (music)|singles]] and four self-released [[demo (music)|demos]] (two of which were recorded under its original name Tyrant).<ref>[http://www.metal-archives.com/band.php?id=35 Encyclopaedia Metallum - Saint Vitus]</ref><ref>[http://www.metal-archives.com/band.php?id=83992 Encyclopaedia Metallum - Tyrant (USA)]</ref>\n\n==Studio albums==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1984\n|'''''[[Saint Vitus (album)|Saint Vitus]]'''''\n* Record label: [[SST Records]]\n* Released: February 1984\n* Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Gramophone record|LP]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette]], [[Digital distribution|digital download]]\n|-\n|1985\n|'''''[[Hallow's Victim]]'''''\n* Record label: SST Records\n* Released: August 1985\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download\n|-\n|1986\n|'''''[[Born Too Late]]'''''\n* Record label: SST Records\n* Released: October 1986\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download\n|-\n|1988\n|'''''[[Mournful Cries]]'''''\n* Record label: SST Records\n* Released: August 22, 1988\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download\n|-\n|1990\n|'''''[[V (Saint Vitus album)|V]]'''''\n* Record label: [[Hellhound Records]]\n* Released: 1990\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download \n|-\n|1992\n|'''''[[C.O.D. (album)|C.O.D.]]'''''\n* Record label: Hellhound Records\n* Released: September 1992\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download \n|-\n|1995\n|'''''[[Die Healing]]'''''\n* Record label: Hellhound Records\n* Released: May 9, 1995\n* Format: CD, LP, cassette, digital download\n|-\n|2012\n|'''''[[Lillie: F-65]]'''''\n* Record label: [[Season of Mist]]\n* Released: April 27, 2012 (Europe)\n* Format: CD, CD+DVD, LP, digital download\n|-\n|2019\n|'''''Saint Vitus'''''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blabbermouth.net/news/listen-to-entire-new-saint-vitus-album-ahead-of-official-release/ |title=Listen To Entire New Saint Vitus Album Ahead Of Official Release |publisher=blabbermouth.net |date=2019-05-16 |accessdate=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n* Record label: Season of Mist\n* Released: May 17, 2019\n* Format: CD, LP, digital download\n|}\n\n==Live albums==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1990\n|'''''[[Live (Saint Vitus album)|Live]]'''''\n* Record label: [[Hellhound Records]]\n* Released: September 1990\n* Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Gramophone record|LP]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette]], [[Digital distribution|digital download]]\n|-\n|2012\n|'''''Marbles in the Moshpit'''''<ref>[http://www.saintvitusband.com/test-post-saint-vitus-website-2 Saint Vitus, official website]</ref>\n* Buried by Time and Dust Records\n* Released: December 2012\n* Format: LP\n|-\n|2016\n|'''''Live Vol. 2'''''\n* Record label: [[Season of Mist]]\n* Released: September 23, 2016\n* Format: CD, LP\n|-\n|}\n\n==Compilation albums==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1991\n|'''''[[Heavier Than Thou]]'''''\n* Record label: [[SST Records]]\n* Released: July 1, 1991\n* Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Gramophone record|LP]], [[Compact Cassette|cassette]], [[Digital distribution|digital download]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Extended plays==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1985\n|'''''[[The Walking Dead (EP)|The Walking Dead]]'''''\n* Record label: [[SST Records]]\n* Released: 1985\n* Format: [[Gramophone record|vinyl]]\n|-\n|1987\n|'''''[[Thirsty and Miserable]]'''''\n* Record label: SST Records\n* Released: 1987\n* Format: Vinyl, [[Compact Cassette|cassette]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Singles==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|1985\n|'''''[[War Is Our Destiny]]'''''\n* Record label: [[SST Records]]\n* Released: 1985\n* Format: [[Gramophone record|12\" vinyl]]\n* Info: Promo, Same track on both sides\n|-\n|2011\n|'''''Saint Vitus/Born Too Late'''''\n* Record label: [[Volcom]]\n* Released: January 2011\n* Format: 7\" Vinyl\n* Info: Recorded live 2009 & 2010\n|-\n|2012\n|'''''[[Blessed Night/Look Behind You]]'''''\n* Record label: [[Season of Mist]]\n* Released: March 2012\n* Format: 7\" Vinyl\n* Info: B-Side is recorded live 2010 \n|-\n|}\n\n==Video albums==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|2007\n|'''''[[Reunion 2003 - Live in Chicago]]'''''\n* Record label: Self-released\n* Released: 2007\n* Format: [[DVD]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Demo albums==\n{| class =\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Album details\n|-\n|1978\n|'''''Rehearsal''''' (as Tyrant)\n* Record label: Self-released\n* Released: 1978\n* Format: [[Compact Cassette|cassette]]\n|-\n|1979\n|'''''Demo 1979''''' (as Tyrant)\n* Record label: Self-released\n* Released: 1979\n* Format: cassette\n|-\n|1983\n|'''''1983 Demo''''' (as Saint Vitus)\n* Record label: Self-released\n* Released: 1983\n* Format: cassette\n|-\n|1992\n|'''''Demo''''' (as Saint Vitus)\n* Record label: Self-released\n* Released: 1992\n* Format: cassette\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Saint Vitus}}\n\n[[Category:Heavy metal group discographies]]\n[[Category:Discographies of American artists]]\n", "name_user": "ReginaldBull", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated the number of studio and live albums", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Vitus_discography"}
{"title_page": "Indian cricket team in Sri Lanka in 1997", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cricket tour\n|  series_name              = Indian cricket team in Sri Lanka in 1997\n|  team1_image              = Flag of India.svg\n|  team1_name               = India\n|  team2_image              = Flag of Sri Lanka.svg\n|  team2_name               = Sri Lanka\n|  from_date                = 2 August\n|  to_date                  = 13 August\n|  team1_captain            =  [[Sachin Tendulkar]]\n|  team2_captain            =  [[Arjuna Ranatunga]]\n|  no_of_tests               = 2\n|  team1_tests_won           = 0\n|  team2_tests_won           = 0\n|  team1_tests_most_runs     = [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (290)\n|  team2_tests_most_runs     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (571)\n|  team1_tests_most_wickets  = [[Anil Kumble]] (5)\n|  team2_tests_most_wickets  = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] (9)\n|  player_of_test_series     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n|  no_of_ODIs               = 3\n|  team1_ODIs_won           = 0\n|  team2_ODIs_won           = 3\n|  team1_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] (211)\n|  team2_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (212)\n|  team1_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] (6)\n|  team2_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (5)\n|  player_of_ODI_series     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n}}\n\nThe [[India national cricket team|Indian cricket team]] toured [[Sri Lanka]] in August 1997, participating in two [[Test cricket|Test matches]] and three [[One Day International]] (ODI) matches. During the first Test match, Sri Lanka scored 952 runs for 6 wickets, the highest team total in Test cricket. Several more records were established in this match, including the highest partnership for the second wicket by [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] and [[Roshan Mahanama]]. The Test series ended without a result, with both Test matches drawn.\n\n[[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] won all three of the One Day International matches, although the third one had to be replayed due to bad weather. Sanath Jayasuriya was the most notable player during the tournament. He was selected as player of the series in both the Test series and the ODI series, and won two-man of the match awards as well. He was the highest scoring batsman during the Test series, and also took the highest number of wickets for Sri Lanka in the ODI series.\n\n==Background==\nThe Indian cricket team had arrived in Sri Lanka on 12 July 1997 to participate in the Asia Cup. After that, they stayed on in the country for two Test matches and three One Day International matches with the Sri Lankan cricket team. The Sri Lankans were the world champions, having won the cricket world cup the previous year, and had also won the Asia Cup, having beaten India in the final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/ARTICLES/ELMO_COMMENT_02AUG1997.html|title=Test Cricket is what the game is all about|last=Rodrigopolle|first=Elmo|date=2 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Tour matches ==\n=== 50-over: Sri Lankan Board President's XI v Indians ===\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 15 August 1997\n| time = \n| daynight = \n| team1 = Sri Lankan Board President's XI\n| team2 = {{cr|IND|name=Indians}}\n| score1 = 240/7 (50 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Russel Arnold]] 56\n| wickets1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 2/29 (5 overs)\n| score2 = 243/8 (49.3 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Rahul Dravid]] 95\n| wickets2 = N Sadikin 2/38 (7 overs)\n| result = Indians won by 2 wickets\n| report = [http://static.espncricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_15AUG1997.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[De Soysa Stadium]], [[Moratuwa]]\n| umpires = \n| motm = \n| toss = Indians won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = \n| notes = \n}}\n\n==Test series==\n[[File:R Premadasa Stadium.jpg|thumb|The R. Premadasa Stadium hosted one Test and two ODI matches.]]\nAlthough only two Test matches had been scheduled for the tour, the Test series turned out to be a significant one in cricketing history. Both were high scoring matches, with the total runs scored in each match exceeding 1,400. Both matches were drawn, but a number of world records were established during the series, particularly in the first match. India played a three-day tour match before the first Test against the [[Sri Lanka Board President's XI]], starting on 29 July. The match ended in a draw, with the Indians scoring 308 runs in their first innings. The President's XI responded with 291, and the Indian team had scored 255 for 5 wickets for their second innings by the end of the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_29-31JUL1997.html|title=India in Sri Lanka (1997): Three day tour match &ndash; Sri Lanka Board President's XI vs India|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> Sanath Jayasuriya was the highest scorer of the series with 571 runs, while Sachin Tendulkar produced 290 runs for the Indians. Muttiah Muralidharan was the highest wicket taker of the series with 9 wickets, followed by Anil Kumble with 5. Both Tests, as well as the practice match, were held in Colombo. The fact that all the matches of the tour were in Colombo was criticized by the media, and the Indian players and officials were also not happy about it. The cricket board had ruled out other venues reportedly due to bad weather.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/ARTICLES/INDIAN_NON_TOUR_19AUG1997.html|title=Indians confined to Colombo: Is it Cricket ?|last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi|date=19 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===First Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 2 \u2013 6 August\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n| team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 537/8[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (167.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Sachin Tendulkar]] 143 (247)\n[[Mohammed Azharuddin]] 126 (199\n[[Navjot Singh Sidhu]] 111 (200)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 3/45 (18 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 952/6[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (271 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 340 (578)\n[[Roshan Mahanama]] 225 (561)\n[[Aravinda de Silva]] 126 (211)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 2/53 (9 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 =\n| runs-team1-inns2 =\n| wickets-team1-inns2 =\n| score-team2-inns2 =\n| runs-team2-inns2 =\n| wickets-team2-inns2 =\n| result = Match drawn\n| venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n| umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[Steve Randell]] (AUS)\n| motm = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n| report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63762.html Scorecard]\n| rain =\n}}\nIndian captain [[Sachin Tendulkar]] won the toss and decided to bat first. Opener [[Nayan Mongia]] got out early with the score on 36. However, [[Navjot Singh Sidhu]] and [[Rahul Dravid]] took the Indians to 183 before Sidhu was caught behind for 111. Dravid then paired up with Tendulkar, but was dismissed by [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] for 69, with the Indian score on 223. [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] then joined Tendulkar on the crease, and the two batsmen put together a formidable partnership and had taken India to 280 runs at the end of the day. On the second day, both batsmen had scored centuries and placed India in a strong position. However, the consistent scoring came to a halt with the wicket of Tendulkar, who was caught on 143 with the team total on 451. [[Sourav Ganguly]] went for a duck soon after, and wickets began to fall at regular intervals. Azharuddin was dismissed for 126 when India was on 479. Two more wickets fell at 516 and 537, and India declared on 537 runs for 8 wickets.<ref name=\"score1test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63762.html|title=India in Sri Lanka Test Series (1997): Scorecard of 1st Test|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"report1test\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_T1_02-06AUG1997_MR.html|title=1st Test: India v Sri Lanka, Match Report|last=Anandappa|first=Ranjan |author2=Thawfeeq, Sa'Adi|date=6 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sanath jayasuriya portrait.jpg|thumb|Sanath Jayasuriya made 340, the first triple century by a Sri Lankan batsman.]]\nThe Sri Lankan openers Sanath Jayasuriya and [[Marvan Atapattu]] went out on to the pitch later in the day. However, Atapattu was caught behind off the very first delivery of debutant [[Nilesh Kulkarni]] for 26. At the close of play on the second day, Sri Lanka were on 39/1, with Jayasuriya not out on 12 and [[Roshan Mahanama]] on the other end. The pair batted throughout the third day and took Sri Lanka to 322/1. Both had scored centuries, and their partnership was at 283 runs. Jayasuriya and Mahanama continued to bat throughout the fourth day as well, and added 265 more to their partnership, taking Sri Lanka to 587/1. Jayasuriya had scored the first triple century by a Sri Lankan batsman, and was followed by Mahanama with a double hundred. Jayasuriya was 50 runs short of the highest individual Test score (375 by [[Brian Lara]]). On the fifth day, a large crowd had gathered at the [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], anticipating a new world record from Jayasuriya. 30,000 were allowed entry free of charge. However, Mahanama was out leg before wicket early in the day for 225 off the bowling of Anil Kumble, when the Sri Lankan score was at 615. Soon after that, Jayasuriya was caught on 340 by Ganguly at silly point off the bowling of [[Rajesh Chauhan]]. However, the scoring continued as captain [[Arjuna Ranatunga]] paired up with [[Aravinda de Silva]] and took the team to 790. When Ranatunga was dismissed for 86, debutant [[Mahela Jayawardene]] joined de Silva at the crease. They took their team's total past 903, Jayawardene scored 66 runs before being dismissed with the Sri Lankan total on 921. With the score on 924, de Silva was dismissed as well, and [[Romesh Kaluwitharana]] and [[Chaminda Vaas]] continued to bat for several more overs. They had taken the total to 952/6 before the innings was declared by the Sri Lankans.<ref name=\"report1test\" /><ref name=\"wcm\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wcm/content/story/334957.html|title=The highest Test total|last=Lynch|first=Steven |date=September 1997|work=Wisden Cricket Monthly|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wisden1test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/153352.html|title=First Test: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Second Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 9 \u2013 12 August\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n| team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 332 (95.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 146 (226)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Debasis Mohanty]] 4/78 (20.4 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 375 (141.1 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 147 (312)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] 4/99 (48 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 415/7[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (98.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 199 (226)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Anil Kumble]] 3/156 (38.4 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 281/5 (100 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] 108 (174)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] 3/96 (35 overs)\n| result = Match drawn\n| venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n| umpires = [[B. C. Cooray]] (SL) & [[Rudi Koertzen]] (SA)\n| motm = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (SL)\n| report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63763.html Scorecard]\n| rain =\n}}\nSachin Tendulkar once again won the toss, but decided to put the Sri Lankans to bat first. The first Sri Lankan wicket fell on 53, when Sanath Jayasuriya, the high scorer of the first Test, was dismissed by debutant [[Debasis Mohanty]] for 32 runs. Marvan Atapattu got out soon after that. Aravinda de Silva joined Roshan Mahanama at the crease and took the Sri Lankans to 121, before Mahanama got out for 37. De Silva continued to bat, although both Arjuna Ranatunga and Mahela Jayawardene were dismissed for 14 and 16 respectively. Romesh Kaluwitharana (6) and Chaminda Vaas (10) also followed, before [[Muttiah Muralidharan]] paired up with de Silva at the end of the day to take the team total to 317. De Silva was finally caught behind the next day for 146, and Muralitharan put up ten more runs on the board before he was dismissed, followed by [[Ravindra Pushpakumara]] for a duck.<ref name=\"score2test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63763.html|title=India in Sri Lanka Test Series (1997): Scorecard of 2nd Test|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIndia got off to a bad start in their first innings, losing their first two wickets before the total had even reached 10. Tendulkar and Sidhu put up a 72 run partnership, before India lost the wicket of Sidhu, followed by Mohommad Azharuddin. However, Sourav Ganguly joined Tendulkar at the crease and the two batsmen took the Indian total to 226/4 by the end of the day. Tendulkar scored a century after being dropped by Arjuna Ranatunga, who was injured in the attempt and had to retire.<ref name=\"report2test\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_T2_09-13AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=2nd Test: India v Sri Lanka, Match Report |date=13 August 1997|work=Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref> On the third day, Ganguly scored a century as well. However, the batsmen after Tendulkar and Ganguly failed to score well, and the Indians were restricted to 375.<ref name=\"score2test\" />\n\nIn the Sri Lankans' second innings, Atapattu was dismissed for 29, and the score was at 77/1 at the end of the day. On the fourth day, Mahanama was dismissed for 35<ref name=\"score2test\" /> but Jayasuriya, who was then joined by Aravinda de Silva, was heading for another big score. The two batsmen put up a 218 run partnership, a new Sri Lankan record for the third wicket. Jayasuriya became the first batsman to reach 1000 runs that year, and at one stage seemed to be reaching the world record for the fastest double century. However, he was bowled out by [[Nilesh Kulkarni]] for 199. De Silva, who had been dropped earlier and bowled by a no ball, ended up with 120, scoring a century in both innings of a match for the second time in his career. The Sri Lankan innings was declared after his wicket fell, with the total at 415/7.<ref name=\"report2test\" /><ref name=\"wisden2test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/292930.html|title=Second Test: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nBeginning the Indians' second innings, opener Ajay Jadeja scored 73 runs, but wickets fell at regular intervals at the other end. Sidhu, Tendulkar and Dravid had been dismissed before the total reached 100, and Jadeja was dismissed with the score on 138.<ref name=\"score2test\" /> However, Mohammad Azharuddin paired up with Ganguly and put up a 110 run stand for the fifth wicket, guiding the Indians out of danger and denying the Sri Lankans the chance of victory. Azharuddin was dropped thrice, and made good use of the chances he got, ending up with an unbeaten 108. The Indians' final score was at 281/5.<ref name=\"report2test\" />\n\n==ODI series==\nThree One Day International matches were originally scheduled for the tour, but the third match had to be replayed the following day since it had to be abandoned due to bad weather.<ref name=\"3odi\" /> As in the Test series, the ODIs were also largely dominated by the batsmen. India played a tour match against the Sri Lankan Board President's XI on 15 August, which they won by 2 wickets. The President's XI had scored 240, and the Indians responded with 243 for 8 wickets in 49.3 overs, with 95 runs coming from Rahul Dravid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_15AUG1997.html|title=India in Sri Lanka (1997): One day tour match &ndash; Sri Lanka Board President's XI vs India|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> The first match created some controversy when the television broadcast showed umpire [[K. T. Francis]] wiping the ball on what appeared to be an Indian flag. However, it later turned out to be a bar towel with the same colours.<ref name=\"wisden1odi\" />\n\n===First ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 17 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n  | score1 = 302/4 (50 overs)\n  | score2 = 300/7 (50 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Marvan Atapattu]] 118 (153)\n  | wickets1 = [[Venkatesh Prasad]] 2/50 (9 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Ajay Jadeja]] 119 (121)\n  | wickets2 = [[Chaminda Vaas]] 3/63 (10 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 2 runs\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64557.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[P. T. Manuel]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Ajay Jadeja]] (IND)\n}}\nTendulkar won the toss and chose to field. The Sri Lankan openers made a partnership of 91 runs in 14 overs, with a quick 73 from Jayasuriya.<ref name=\"wisden1odi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151631.html|title=First One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> After he was bowled out, Atapattu and Mahanama took the Sri Lankan score to 199 before Mahanama was dismissed for 53. Aravinda de Silva paired up with Atapattu to take the total to 279, before he was dismissed. Atapattu, who made his maiden century, was run out for 118 and the Sri Lankans ended their innings with a total of 302/4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64557.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 1st ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Indian openers made a stand of 58 runs until the dismissal of Sourav Ganguly, but wickets began to fall rapidly after that. The Indian total was at 64/4 at the eleventh over when Ajay Jadeja joined Mohammad Azharuddin at the crease. These two batsmen took the Indians to safety with a record partnership of 232 runs, and took India to 287 before Jadeja was dismissed by Vaas for 119. Both Mongia and Chauhan got out in quick succession, and Azharuddin was left with the task of getting 5 runs off the last delivery of the match. However, he only managed 2, and the Indians ended up with 300 runs, just 3 short of the required target. Azharuddin remained unbeaten on 111.<ref name=\"1odi\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI1_17AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Sri Lanka in thrilling two-run win over India|last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi |date=17 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Second ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 20 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n  | score1 = 238 (49.3 overs)\n  | score2 = 241/3 (41.5 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 113 (126)\n  | wickets1 = [[Upul Chandana]] 3/32 (8 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 66 (56)\n  | wickets2 = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] 1/35 (7 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 7 wickets\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64558.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[BC Cooray]] (SL) & [[Nandasena Pathirana]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n}}\nThe Sri Lankans won the toss and decided to field first, and got an early breakthrough when Tendulkar was dismissed for 6. However, Sourav Ganguly and Robin Singh took the Indians to 105 before Singh was dismissed as the second wicket. Azharuddin and Dravid also got out without scoring much, leaving the Indians at 159/4. Jadeja and Ganguly then built up a partnership and took the total to 218, with Ganguly scoring his maiden century. However, the last six wickets fell within 26 runs, and the final Indian score was at 238.<ref name=\"wisden2odi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151632.html|title=Second One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"2odiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64558.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 2nd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nJayasuriya and Atapattu made a good partnership again, taking their team to 79. After Atapattu was dismissed for 38, Jayasuriya paired up with Mahanama to take the Sri Lankans to 130, before he was dismissed for 66. Mahanama was run out for 66 when the team total was on 219, but Aravinda de Silva and Upul Chandana guided the Sri Lankan team to victory in 41 overs, the former scoring a half century as well.<ref name=\"wisden2odi\" /><ref name=\"2odiscore\" />\n\n===Third ODI shortened due to rain\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 23 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n  | score1 = 291/9 (50 overs)\n  | score2 = 132/6 (19 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Robin Singh (cricketer, born 1963)|Robin Singh]] 100 (102)\n  | wickets1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 3/55 (10 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 68 (38)\n  | wickets2 = [[Robin Singh (cricketer, born 1963)|Robin Singh]] 3/20 (4 overs)\n  | result = No result\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64559.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[T. M. Samarasinghe]] (SL)\n  | motm =\n  | rain = Rain interrupted the match, and Sri Lanka were given a target of 195 in 25 overs. However, the match was stopped after 19 overs due to bad light. A decision was made to replay the match on 24 August.\n}}\nThe Sri Lankans having won the toss and put the Indians to bat, had them in a difficult position early when both their openers were out with the total on 44.<ref name=\"3aodiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64559.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 3rd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> However, Robin Singh and Rahul Dravid built up a strong partnership and took their team to a total of 206 runs, before Dravid was out for 78. Singh had just completed his maiden century when he was dismissed. Azharuddin had become the third batsman to pass 7,000 ODI runs before he was dismissed for 34 with the total on 273. The rest of the batsmen scored low, with the last six wickets being taken by the Sri Lankans in 33 balls while conceding 23 runs. The Indians completed their 50 overs with a score of 291/9.<ref name=\"3odi\" />\n\nContinuing his good form from the previous matches, Jayasuriya knocked a fast 68 at a strike rate of 178.94.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" /> The match was interrupted by rain during the eighth over, and after resuming it with a reduced target of 195 in 25 overs, Jayasuriya and Atapattu were dismissed with the score on 85 and 96 respectively. Ranatunga, Mahanama, and Kalpage all lost their wickets early to Robin Singh in their search for quick runs. Aravinda de Silva attempted to salvage the Sri Lankan innings, before he too was dismissed for 22. The Sri Lankan team were on 132/6 when bad light stopped play at about 6.05&nbsp;pm after 19 overs,<ref name=\"3odi\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI3-ABAN_23AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Bad weather forces third one-dayer to be abandoned |last=Anandappa|first=Ranjan |date=23 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> possibly denying India the chance of a win. The match was scheduled to be replayed the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151633.html|title=Third One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Third ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 24 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n  | score1 = 264 (49.4 overs)\n  | score2 = 255/8 (50 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 104 (117)\n  | wickets1 = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] 4/43 (8.4 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] 65 (68)\n  | wickets2 = [[Sajeewa de Silva]] 2/48 (8 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 9 runs\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64560.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[T. M. Samarasinghe]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (SL)\n}}\nThe Indians won the toss and chose to field, and immediately got themselves in an advantageous position after dismissing both Sri Lankan openers for 3 runs each. However, an 83 run partnership between Roshan Mahanama and Aravinda de Silva took the Sri Lankans out of danger and onto a score of 105, before Mahanama was bowled out for 50.<ref name=\"3odiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64560.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 3rd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> Ranatunga was quickly dismissed as well, but de Silva put up an 82 run stand with [[Lanka de Silva]] who made his maiden half century, and scored 114 runs himself.<ref name=\"wrapup\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI3_24AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Lanka wrap up one day series: win third one-dayer by nine runs |last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi|date=24 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> The Sri Lankans were all out for 264 in the last over.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" />\n\nIndia started well with a 50 run opening partnership with 39 from Sachin Tendulkar.<ref name=\"wrapup\" /> Robin Singh and Rahul Dravid contributed with 28 and 42 respectively.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" /> Mohammad Azharuddin and Ajay Jadeja took the Indians to 221 for 4 wickets, but both were then run out, the former with a score of 65. After that, the Sri Lankan team kept their fielding tight and restricted the Indians to a total of 255 at the end of the allotted 50 overs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151634.html|title=Fourth One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{International cricket tours of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Cricket Team in Sri Lanka in 1997}}\n[[Category:1997 in Indian cricket]]\n[[Category:1997 in Sri Lankan cricket]]\n[[Category:International cricket competitions from 1994\u201395 to 1997]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket tours of Sri Lanka|1997]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan cricket seasons from 1972\u201373 to 1999\u20132000]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cricket tour\n|  series_name              = Indian cricket team in Sri Lanka in 1997\n|  team1_image              = Flag of India.svg\n|  team1_name               = India\n|  team2_image              = Flag of Sri Lanka.svg\n|  team2_name               = Sri Lanka\n|  from_date                = 2 August\n|  to_date                  = 13 August\n|  team1_captain            =  [[Sachin Tendulkar]]\n|  team2_captain            =  [[Arjuna Ranatunga]]\n|  no_of_tests               = 2\n|  team1_tests_won           = 0\n|  team2_tests_won           = 0\n|  team1_tests_most_runs     = [[Sachin Tendulkar]] (290)\n|  team2_tests_most_runs     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (571)\n|  team1_tests_most_wickets  = [[Anil Kumble]] (5)\n|  team2_tests_most_wickets  = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] (9)\n|  player_of_test_series     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n|  no_of_ODIs               = 3\n|  team1_ODIs_won           = 0\n|  team2_ODIs_won           = 3\n|  team1_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] (211)\n|  team2_ODIs_most_runs     = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (212)\n|  team1_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] (6)\n|  team2_ODIs_most_wickets  = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (5)\n|  player_of_ODI_series     = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n}}\n\nThe [[India national cricket team|Indian cricket team]] toured [[Sri Lanka]] in August 1997, participating in two [[Test cricket|Test matches]] and three [[One Day International]] (ODI) matches. During the first Test match, Sri Lanka scored 952 runs for 6 wickets, the highest team total in Test cricket. Several more records were established in this match, including the highest partnership for the second wicket by [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] and [[Roshan Mahanama]]. The Test series ended without a result, with both Test matches drawn.\n\n[[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] won all three of the One Day International matches, although the third one had to be replayed due to bad weather. Sanath Jayasuriya was the most notable player during the tournament. He was selected as player of the series in both the Test series and the ODI series, and won two-man of the match awards as well. He was the highest scoring batsman during the Test series, and also took the highest number of wickets for Sri Lanka in the ODI series.\n\n==Background==\nThe Indian cricket team had arrived in Sri Lanka on 12 July 1997 to participate in the Asia Cup. After that, they stayed on in the country for two Test matches and three One Day International matches with the Sri Lankan cricket team. The Sri Lankans were the world champions, having won the cricket world cup the previous year, and had also won the Asia Cup, having beaten India in the final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/ARTICLES/ELMO_COMMENT_02AUG1997.html|title=Test Cricket is what the game is all about|last=Rodrigopolle|first=Elmo|date=2 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Tour matches ==\n=== 50-over: Sri Lankan Board President's XI v Indians ===\n{{Single-innings cricket match\n| date = 15 August 1997\n| time = \n| daynight = \n| team1 = Sri Lankan Board President's XI\n| team2 = {{cr|IND|name=Indians}}\n| score1 = 240/7 (50 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Russel Arnold]] 56\n| wickets1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 2/29 (5 overs)\n| score2 = 243/8 (49.3 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Rahul Dravid]] 95\n| wickets2 = N Sadikin 2/38 (7 overs)\n| result = Indians won by 2 wickets\n| report = [http://static.espncricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_15AUG1997.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[De Soysa Stadium]], [[Moratuwa]]\n| umpires = \n| motm = \n| toss = Indians won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = \n| notes = \n}}\n\n==Test series==\n[[File:R Premadasa Stadium.jpg|thumb|The R. Premadasa Stadium hosted one Test and two ODI matches.]]\nAlthough only two Test matches had been scheduled for the tour, the Test series turned out to be a significant one in cricketing history. Both were high scoring matches, with the total runs scored in each match exceeding 1,400. Both matches were drawn, but a number of world records were established during the series, particularly in the first match. India played a three-day tour match before the first Test against the [[Sri Lanka Board President's XI]], starting on 29 July. The match ended in a draw, with the Indians scoring 308 runs in their first innings. The President's XI responded with 291, and the Indian team had scored 255 for 5 wickets for their second innings by the end of the match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_29-31JUL1997.html|title=India in Sri Lanka (1997): Three day tour match &ndash; Sri Lanka Board President's XI vs India|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> Sanath Jayasuriya was the highest scorer of the series with 571 runs, while Sachin Tendulkar produced 290 runs for the Indians. Muttiah Muralidharan was the highest wicket taker of the series with 9 wickets, followed by Anil Kumble with 5. Both Tests, as well as the practice match, were held in Colombo. The fact that all the matches of the tour were in Colombo was criticized by the media, and the Indian players and officials were also not happy about it. The cricket board had ruled out other venues reportedly due to bad weather.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/ARTICLES/INDIAN_NON_TOUR_19AUG1997.html|title=Indians confined to Colombo: Is it Cricket ?|last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi|date=19 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===First Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 2 \u2013 6 August\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n| team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 537/8[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (167.3 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Sachin Tendulkar]] 143 (247)\n[[Mohammed Azharuddin]] 126 (199\n[[Navjot Singh Sidhu]] 111 (200)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 3/45 (18 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 952/6[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (271 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 340 (578)\n[[Roshan Mahanama]] 225 (561)\n[[Aravinda de Silva]] 126 (211)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 2/53 (9 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 =\n| runs-team1-inns2 =\n| wickets-team1-inns2 =\n| score-team2-inns2 =\n| runs-team2-inns2 =\n| wickets-team2-inns2 =\n| result = Match drawn\n| venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n| umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[Steve Randell]] (AUS)\n| motm = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n| report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63762.html Scorecard]\n| rain =\n}}\nIndian captain [[Sachin Tendulkar]] won the toss and decided to bat first. Opener [[Nayan Mongia]] got out early with the score on 36. However, [[Navjot Singh Sidhu]] and [[Rahul Dravid]] took the Indians to 183 before Sidhu was caught behind for 111. Dravid then paired up with Tendulkar, but was dismissed by [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] for 69, with the Indian score on 223. [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] then joined Tendulkar on the crease, and the two batsmen put together a formidable partnership and had taken India to 280 runs at the end of the day. On the second day, both batsmen had scored centuries and placed India in a strong position. However, the consistent scoring came to a halt with the wicket of Tendulkar, who was caught on 143 with the team total on 451. [[Sourav Ganguly]] went for a duck soon after, and wickets began to fall at regular intervals. Azharuddin was dismissed for 126 when India was on 479. Two more wickets fell at 516 and 537, and India declared on 537 runs for 8 wickets.<ref name=\"score1test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63762.html|title=India in Sri Lanka Test Series (1997): Scorecard of 1st Test|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"report1test\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_T1_02-06AUG1997_MR.html|title=1st Test: India v Sri Lanka, Match Report|last=Anandappa|first=Ranjan |author2=Thawfeeq, Sa'Adi|date=6 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sanath jayasuriya portrait.jpg|thumb|Sanath Jayasuriya made 340, the first triple century by a Sri Lankan batsman.]]\nThe Sri Lankan openers Sanath Jayasuriya and [[Marvan Atapattu]] went out on to the pitch later in the day. However, Atapattu was caught behind off the very first delivery of debutant [[Nilesh Kulkarni]] for 26. At the close of play on the second day, Sri Lanka were on 39/1, with Jayasuriya not out on 12 and [[Roshan Mahanama]] on the other end. The pair batted throughout the third day and took Sri Lanka to 322/1. Both had scored centuries, and their partnership was at 283 runs. Jayasuriya and Mahanama continued to bat throughout the fourth day as well, and added 265 more to their partnership, taking Sri Lanka to 587/1. Jayasuriya had scored the first triple century by a Sri Lankan batsman, and was followed by Mahanama with a double hundred. Jayasuriya was 50 runs short of the highest individual Test score (375 by [[Brian Lara]]). On the fifth day, a large crowd had gathered at the [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], anticipating a new world record from Jayasuriya. 30,000 were allowed entry free of charge. However, Mahanama was out leg before wicket early in the day for 225 off the bowling of Anil Kumble, when the Sri Lankan score was at 615. Soon after that, Jayasuriya was caught on 340 by Ganguly at silly point off the bowling of [[Rajesh Chauhan]]. However, the scoring continued as captain [[Arjuna Ranatunga]] paired up with [[Aravinda de Silva]] and took the team to 790. When Ranatunga was dismissed for 86, debutant [[Mahela Jayawardene]] joined de Silva at the crease. They took their team's total past 903, Jayawardene scored 66 runs before being dismissed with the Sri Lankan total on 921. With the score on 924, de Silva was dismissed as well, and [[Romesh Kaluwitharana]] and [[Chaminda Vaas]] continued to bat for several more overs. They had taken the total to 952/6 before the innings was declared by the Sri Lankans.<ref name=\"report1test\" /><ref name=\"wcm\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wcm/content/story/334957.html|title=The highest Test total|last=Lynch|first=Steven |date=September 1997|work=Wisden Cricket Monthly|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wisden1test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/153352.html|title=First Test: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Second Test===\n{{Test match\n| date = 9 \u2013 12 August\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n| team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n| score-team1-inns1 = 332 (95.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 146 (226)\n| wickets-team1-inns1 = [[Debasis Mohanty]] 4/78 (20.4 overs)\n| score-team2-inns1 = 375 (141.1 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 147 (312)\n| wickets-team2-inns1 = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] 4/99 (48 overs)\n| score-team1-inns2 = 415/7[[Declaration and forfeiture|d]] (98.4 overs)\n| runs-team1-inns2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 199 (226)\n| wickets-team1-inns2 = [[Anil Kumble]] 3/156 (38.4 overs)\n| score-team2-inns2 = 281/5 (100 overs)\n| runs-team2-inns2 = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] 108 (174)\n| wickets-team2-inns2 = [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] 3/96 (35 overs)\n| result = Match drawn\n| venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n| umpires = [[B. C. Cooray]] (SL) & [[Rudi Koertzen]] (SA)\n| motm = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (SL)\n| report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63763.html Scorecard]\n| rain =\n}}\nSachin Tendulkar once again won the toss, but decided to put the Sri Lankans to bat first. The first Sri Lankan wicket fell on 53, when Sanath Jayasuriya, the high scorer of the first Test, was dismissed by debutant [[Debasis Mohanty]] for 32 runs. Marvan Atapattu got out soon after that. Aravinda de Silva joined Roshan Mahanama at the crease and took the Sri Lankans to 121, before Mahanama got out for 37. De Silva continued to bat, although both Arjuna Ranatunga and Mahela Jayawardene were dismissed for 14 and 16 respectively. Romesh Kaluwitharana (6) and Chaminda Vaas (10) also followed, before [[Muttiah Muralidharan]] paired up with de Silva at the end of the day to take the team total to 317. De Silva was finally caught behind the next day for 146, and Muralitharan put up ten more runs on the board before he was dismissed, followed by [[Ravindra Pushpakumara]] for a duck.<ref name=\"score2test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/63763.html|title=India in Sri Lanka Test Series (1997): Scorecard of 2nd Test|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIndia got off to a bad start in their first innings, losing their first two wickets before the total had even reached 10. Tendulkar and Sidhu put up a 72 run partnership, before India lost the wicket of Sidhu, followed by Mohommad Azharuddin. However, Sourav Ganguly joined Tendulkar at the crease and the two batsmen took the Indian total to 226/4 by the end of the day. Tendulkar scored a century after being dropped by Arjuna Ranatunga, who was injured in the attempt and had to retire.<ref name=\"report2test\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_T2_09-13AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=2nd Test: India v Sri Lanka, Match Report |date=13 August 1997|work=Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref> On the third day, Ganguly scored a century as well. However, the batsmen after Tendulkar and Ganguly failed to score well, and the Indians were restricted to 375.<ref name=\"score2test\" />\n\nIn the Sri Lankans' second innings, Atapattu was dismissed for 29, and the score was at 77/1 at the end of the day. On the fourth day, Mahanama was dismissed for 35<ref name=\"score2test\" /> but Jayasuriya, who was then joined by Aravinda de Silva, was heading for another big score. The two batsmen put up a 218 run partnership, a new Sri Lankan record for the third wicket. Jayasuriya became the first batsman to reach 1000 runs that year, and at one stage seemed to be reaching the world record for the fastest double century. However, he was bowled out by [[Nilesh Kulkarni]] for 199. De Silva, who had been dropped earlier and bowled by a no ball, ended up with 120, scoring a century in both innings of a match for the second time in his career. The Sri Lankan innings was declared after his wicket fell, with the total at 415/7.<ref name=\"report2test\" /><ref name=\"wisden2test\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/292930.html|title=Second Test: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=8 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nBeginning the Indians' second innings, opener Ajay Jadeja scored 73 runs, but wickets fell at regular intervals at the other end. Sidhu, Tendulkar and Dravid had been dismissed before the total reached 100, and Jadeja was dismissed with the score on 138.<ref name=\"score2test\" /> However, Mohammad Azharuddin paired up with Ganguly and put up a 110 run stand for the fifth wicket, guiding the Indians out of danger and denying the Sri Lankans the chance of victory. Azharuddin was dropped thrice, and made good use of the chances he got, ending up with an unbeaten 108. The Indians' final score was at 281/5.<ref name=\"report2test\" />\n\n==ODI series==\nThree One Day International matches were originally scheduled for the tour, but the third match had to be replayed the following day since it had to be abandoned due to bad weather.<ref name=\"3odi\" /> As in the Test series, the ODIs were also largely dominated by the batsmen. India played a tour match against the Sri Lankan Board President's XI on 15 August, which they won by 2 wickets. The President's XI had scored 240, and the Indians responded with 243 for 8 wickets in 49.3 overs, with 95 runs coming from Rahul Dravid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL-BPRES-XI_15AUG1997.html|title=India in Sri Lanka (1997): One day tour match &ndash; Sri Lanka Board President's XI vs India|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> The first match created some controversy when the television broadcast showed umpire [[K. T. Francis]] wiping the ball on what appeared to be an Indian flag. However, it later turned out to be a bar towel with the same colours.<ref name=\"wisden1odi\" />\n\n===First ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 17 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n  | score1 = 302/4 (50 overs)\n  | score2 = 300/7 (50 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Marvan Atapattu]] 118 (153)\n  | wickets1 = [[Venkatesh Prasad]] 2/50 (9 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Ajay Jadeja]] 119 (121)\n  | wickets2 = [[Chaminda Vaas]] 3/63 (10 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 2 runs\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64557.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[P. T. Manuel]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Ajay Jadeja]] (IND)\n}}\nTendulkar won the toss and chose to field. The Sri Lankan openers made a partnership of 91 runs in 14 overs, with a quick 73 from Jayasuriya.<ref name=\"wisden1odi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151631.html|title=First One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> After he was bowled out, Atapattu and Mahanama took the Sri Lankan score to 199 before Mahanama was dismissed for 53. Aravinda de Silva paired up with Atapattu to take the total to 279, before he was dismissed. Atapattu, who made his maiden century, was run out for 118 and the Sri Lankans ended their innings with a total of 302/4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64557.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 1st ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Indian openers made a stand of 58 runs until the dismissal of Sourav Ganguly, but wickets began to fall rapidly after that. The Indian total was at 64/4 at the eleventh over when Ajay Jadeja joined Mohammad Azharuddin at the crease. These two batsmen took the Indians to safety with a record partnership of 232 runs, and took India to 287 before Jadeja was dismissed by Vaas for 119. Both Mongia and Chauhan got out in quick succession, and Azharuddin was left with the task of getting 5 runs off the last delivery of the match. However, he only managed 2, and the Indians ended up with 300 runs, just 3 short of the required target. Azharuddin remained unbeaten on 111.<ref name=\"1odi\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI1_17AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Sri Lanka in thrilling two-run win over India|last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi |date=17 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Second ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 20 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n  | score1 = 238 (49.3 overs)\n  | score2 = 241/3 (41.5 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Sourav Ganguly]] 113 (126)\n  | wickets1 = [[Upul Chandana]] 3/32 (8 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 66 (56)\n  | wickets2 = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] 1/35 (7 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 7 wickets\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64558.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[R. Premadasa Stadium]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[BC Cooray]] (SL) & [[Nandasena Pathirana]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] (SL)\n}}\nThe Sri Lankans won the toss and decided to field first, and got an early breakthrough when Tendulkar was dismissed for 6. However, Sourav Ganguly and Robin Singh took the Indians to 105 before Singh was dismissed as the second wicket. Azharuddin and Dravid also got out without scoring much, leaving the Indians at 159/4. Jadeja and Ganguly then built up a partnership and took the total to 218, with Ganguly scoring his maiden century. However, the last six wickets fell within 26 runs, and the final Indian score was at 238.<ref name=\"wisden2odi\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151632.html|title=Second One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden |publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"2odiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64558.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 2nd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=7 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nJayasuriya and Atapattu made a good partnership again, taking their team to 79. After Atapattu was dismissed for 38, Jayasuriya paired up with Mahanama to take the Sri Lankans to 130, before he was dismissed for 66. Mahanama was run out for 66 when the team total was on 219, but Aravinda de Silva and Upul Chandana guided the Sri Lankan team to victory in 41 overs, the former scoring a half century as well.<ref name=\"wisden2odi\" /><ref name=\"2odiscore\" />\n\n===Third ODI (abandoned)===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 23 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|IND}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|Sri Lanka}}\n  | score1 = 291/9 (50 overs)\n  | score2 = 132/6 (19 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Robin Singh (cricketer, born 1963)|Robin Singh]] 100 (102)\n  | wickets1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 3/55 (10 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Sanath Jayasuriya]] 68 (38)\n  | wickets2 = [[Robin Singh (cricketer, born 1963)|Robin Singh]] 3/20 (4 overs)\n  | result = No result\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64559.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[T. M. Samarasinghe]] (SL)\n  | motm =\n  | rain = Rain interrupted the match, and Sri Lanka were given a target of 195 in 25 overs. However, the match was stopped after 19 overs due to bad light. A decision was made to replay the match on 24 August.\n}}\nThe Sri Lankans having won the toss and put the Indians to bat, had them in a difficult position early when both their openers were out with the total on 44.<ref name=\"3aodiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64559.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 3rd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> However, Robin Singh and Rahul Dravid built up a strong partnership and took their team to a total of 206 runs, before Dravid was out for 78. Singh had just completed his maiden century when he was dismissed. Azharuddin had become the third batsman to pass 7,000 ODI runs before he was dismissed for 34 with the total on 273. The rest of the batsmen scored low, with the last six wickets being taken by the Sri Lankans in 33 balls while conceding 23 runs. The Indians completed their 50 overs with a score of 291/9.<ref name=\"3odi\" />\n\nContinuing his good form from the previous matches, Jayasuriya knocked a fast 68 at a strike rate of 178.94.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" /> The match was interrupted by rain during the eighth over, and after resuming it with a reduced target of 195 in 25 overs, Jayasuriya and Atapattu were dismissed with the score on 85 and 96 respectively. Ranatunga, Mahanama, and Kalpage all lost their wickets early to Robin Singh in their search for quick runs. Aravinda de Silva attempted to salvage the Sri Lankan innings, before he too was dismissed for 22. The Sri Lankan team were on 132/6 when bad light stopped play at about 6.05&nbsp;pm after 19 overs,<ref name=\"3odi\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI3-ABAN_23AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Bad weather forces third one-dayer to be abandoned |last=Anandappa|first=Ranjan |date=23 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> possibly denying India the chance of a win. The match was scheduled to be replayed the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151633.html|title=Third One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Third ODI===\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 24 August\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|Sri Lanka}}\n  | team2 = {{cr|IND}}\n  | score1 = 264 (49.4 overs)\n  | score2 = 255/8 (50 overs)\n  | runs1 = [[Aravinda de Silva]] 104 (117)\n  | wickets1 = [[Abey Kuruvilla]] 4/43 (8.4 overs)\n  | runs2 = [[Mohammad Azharuddin]] 65 (68)\n  | wickets2 = [[Sajeewa de Silva]] 2/48 (8 overs)\n  | result = Sri Lanka won by 9 runs\n  | report = [http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64560.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = [[Sinhalese Sports Club Ground]], [[Colombo]]\n  | umpires = [[K. T. Francis]] (SL) & [[T. M. Samarasinghe]] (SL)\n  | motm = [[Aravinda de Silva]] (SL)\n}}\nThe Indians won the toss and chose to field, and immediately got themselves in an advantageous position after dismissing both Sri Lankan openers for 3 runs each. However, an 83 run partnership between Roshan Mahanama and Aravinda de Silva took the Sri Lankans out of danger and onto a score of 105, before Mahanama was bowled out for 50.<ref name=\"3odiscore\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/64560.html|title=India in Sri Lanka ODI Series (1997): Scorecard of 3rd ODI|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> Ranatunga was quickly dismissed as well, but de Silva put up an 82 run stand with [[Lanka de Silva]] who made his maiden half century, and scored 114 runs himself.<ref name=\"wrapup\">{{Cite news|url=http://static.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1997-98/IND_IN_SL/IND_SL_ODI3_24AUG1997_DAILY_MR.html|title=Lanka wrap up one day series: win third one-dayer by nine runs |last=Thawfeeq|first=Sa'Adi|date=24 August 1997|work=The Daily News|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref> The Sri Lankans were all out for 264 in the last over.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" />\n\nIndia started well with a 50 run opening partnership with 39 from Sachin Tendulkar.<ref name=\"wrapup\" /> Robin Singh and Rahul Dravid contributed with 28 and 42 respectively.<ref name=\"3odiscore\" /> Mohammad Azharuddin and Ajay Jadeja took the Indians to 221 for 4 wickets, but both were then run out, the former with a score of 65. After that, the Sri Lankan team kept their fielding tight and restricted the Indians to a total of 255 at the end of the allotted 50 overs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/151634.html|title=Fourth One-Day International: Sri Lanka vs India|work=Wisden|publisher=Cricinfo|accessdate=6 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{International cricket tours of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Cricket Team in Sri Lanka in 1997}}\n[[Category:1997 in Indian cricket]]\n[[Category:1997 in Sri Lankan cricket]]\n[[Category:International cricket competitions from 1994\u201395 to 1997]]\n[[Category:Indian cricket tours of Sri Lanka|1997]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan cricket seasons from 1972\u201373 to 1999\u20132000]]\n", "name_user": "103.18.168.150", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eThird ODI (abandoned))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_cricket_team_in_Sri_Lanka_in_1997"}
{"title_page": "The Matrix Revolutions", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = The Matrix Revolutions\n| image                = Matrix revolutions ver7.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[The Wachowskis]]<!--Do not change without consensus. See [[Talk:The Matrix (franchise)#Request for Comment - Crediting The Wachowskis]]. -->{{efn|name=Credited|Credited as ''The Wachowski Brothers''.}}\n| producer             = [[Joel Silver]]\n| writer               = The Wachowskis\n| based on             = [[The Matrix (franchise)|Characters]]<br />by The Wachowskis\n| starring             = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keanu Reeves]]\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]]\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]]\n* [[Hugo Weaving]]\n* [[Jada Pinkett Smith]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]]\n| cinematography       = [[Bill Pope]]\n| editing              = [[Zach Staenberg]]\n| production companies = {{Plain list|\n* [[Village Roadshow Pictures]]\n* NPV Entertainment\n* [[Silver Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released             = {{Film date|2003|11|05|}}\n| runtime              = 129 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 128:48--><ref>{{cite web |title=The Matrix Revolutions |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/matrix-revolutions-2003 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=September 15, 2013}}</ref>\n| country              = United States<ref name=\"Lumiere\">{{cite web |title=''The Matrix Revolutions'' (2003) |url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=20284 |work=[[Lumiere (website)|Lumiere]] |accessdate=November 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/452404/Matrix-Revolutions-The/</ref>\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $110\u2013150 million<ref name=\"Allmovie (2010, The Matrix Revolutions)\" /><ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n| gross                = $427.3 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=matrixrevolutions.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Matrix Revolutions''''' is a 2003 American [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[action film]] written and directed by [[the Wachowskis]].{{efn|name=Credited}}<!--Do not change without consensus. See [[Talk:The Matrix (franchise)#Request for Comment - Crediting The Wachowskis]]. --> It was the third <!-- Please do not add \"and final\"; this is self-explanatory --> installment of [[The Matrix (franchise)|''The Matrix'' film franchise]], released six months following ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]''. The film was released simultaneously in 60 countries on November 5, 2003. While being the final entry in the original trilogy of the series, the ''Matrix'' storyline is continued in ''[[The Matrix Online]]''. It was the first live-action feature film to be released in both regular and [[IMAX]] theaters at the same time. Despite having a mixed reception from critics, the film grossed $427.3 million worldwide. A [[The Matrix 4|fourth ''Matrix'' film]] began production in February 2020.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- PER WP:FILM PLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES FOR FEATURE-LENGTH FILMS SHOULD BE BETWEEN 400 AND 700 WORDS.-->\n[[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]] and [[Bane (The Matrix)|Bane]] lie unconscious in the medical bay of the ship ''Hammer''. Inside the Matrix, Neo is trapped in a [[subway station]] named Mobil Ave (an anagram for [[limbo]]), a transition zone between the Matrix and the Machine City. He meets a \"family\" of programs, including a girl named Sati. The \"father\" tells Neo the subway is controlled by the Trainman, a program loyal to the [[Merovingian (The Matrix)|Merovingian]]. When Neo tries to board a train with the family, the Trainman refuses and overpowers him.\n\n[[Seraph (The Matrix)|Seraph]] contacts [[Morpheus (The Matrix)|Morpheus]] and [[Trinity (The Matrix)|Trinity]] on behalf of the [[Oracle (The Matrix)|Oracle]], who informs them of Neo's confinement. Seraph, Morpheus and Trinity enter [[Club Hel]], where they confront the Merovingian and force him to release Neo. Troubled by visions of the Machine City, Neo visits the Oracle, who reveals that [[Agent Smith|Smith]] intends to destroy both the Matrix and the real world. She states that \"everything that has a beginning has an end,\" and that the war will conclude. After Neo leaves, a large group of Smiths assimilates Sati and Seraph. One assimilates the Oracle and gains her powers of [[precognition]].\n\nIn the real world, the crews of the ''[[Nebuchadnezzar (The Matrix)|Nebuchadnezzar]]'' and the ''Hammer'' find and reactivate [[Niobe (The Matrix)|Niobe's]] ship, the ''Logos''. They interrogate Bane, who says that he has no recollection of the earlier massacre. As the captains plan their defense of Zion, Neo requests a ship to travel to the Machine City. Motivated by her [[Enter the Matrix|encounter with the Oracle]], Niobe offers him the ''Logos''. Neo departs, accompanied by Trinity. Bane, who has stowed away on the ''Logos'', takes Trinity hostage. Neo realizes that Bane has been assimilated by Smith and a fight ensues. Bane burns Neo's eyes with a power cable, permanently blinding him. Neo, discovering an ability to perceive anything part of the machine source code in the real world as wreathed in golden light, sees and kills Bane. Trinity pilots them to the Machine City.\n\nNiobe and Morpheus rush toward Zion in the ''Hammer'' to aid the human defenses. Zion's shipyard is overwhelmed by a horde of Sentinels, and the fatally wounded [[Captain Mifune]] instructs [[Kid (The Matrix)|Kid]] to open the gate for the ''Hammer''. When it arrives, it discharges its [[Electromagnetic pulse|EMP]], disabling all the Sentinels present but also Zion's remaining defenses. The humans are forced to retreat and wait for the next attack, thinking it will be their last stand.\n\nNear the Machine City, the ''Logos'' is bombarded by thousands of missiles, causing it to crash, fatally wounding Trinity. She dies in Neo's arms. Neo enters the Machine City and encounters \"Deus Ex Machina,\" the machine leader. Neo warns that Smith plans to conquer both the Matrix and the real world and offers to stop Smith in exchange for peace with Zion. The machine leader agrees, and the Sentinels stop attacking Zion.\n\nThe Machines provide a connection for Neo to enter the Matrix. Inside, the Smith with the Oracle's powers steps forth, saying that he has foreseen his victory against Neo. After a protracted battle, Neo realizes there is no other way to win and allows himself to be assimilated. The machine leader sends a surge of energy into Neo's body in the real world. Because Neo is connected to the Source, the energy surge causes the Neo-Smith clone and all other Smith clones in the Matrix to be destroyed, deleting Smith once and for all. The Sentinels withdraw from Zion, Morpheus and Niobe embrace, and Neo sees a final vision of the machine city while seemingly succumbing to his injuries, as his body is carried away by the machines.\n\nThe Matrix is rebooted, and the Architect encounters the Oracle in a park. They agree that the peace will last \"as long as it can\" and that all humans will be offered the opportunity to leave the Matrix. When questioned about Neo's fate, the Oracle tells Sati that she thinks they will see Neo again as Sati reveals she created a beautiful sunrise over the horizon in Neo's honor. Seraph asks the Oracle if she knew this would happen. She replies that she did not know, but she believed.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Keanu Reeves]] as [[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]]\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]] as [[Morpheus (The Matrix)|Morpheus]]\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] as [[Trinity (The Matrix)|Trinity]]\n* [[Hugo Weaving]] as [[Agent Smith]]\n** [[Ian Bliss]] as Bane\n* [[Jada Pinkett Smith]] as [[Niobe (The Matrix)|Niobe]]\n* [[Mary Alice]] as [[The Oracle (The Matrix)|The Oracle]]\n* [[Harold Perrineau]] as Link\n* [[Monica Bellucci]] as [[Persephone (The Matrix)|Persephone]]\n* [[Harry J. Lennix]] as Commander Lock\n* [[Lambert Wilson]] as Merovingian\n* [[Nona Gaye]] as Zee\n* [[Anthony Zerbe]] as Councillor Hamann\n* [[Nathaniel Lees]] as Captain Mifune\n* [[Collin Chou]] as [[Seraph (The Matrix)|Seraph]]\n* [[Helmut Bakaitis]] as [[Architect (The Matrix)|The Architect]]\n* [[Tanveer K. Atwal]] as Sati\n* [[Bruce Spence]] as The Trainman\n* [[Gina Torres]] as Cas\n* [[Clayton Watson]] as Kid\n* [[Cornel West]] as Councillor West\n* [[Bernard White (actor)|Bernard White]] as Ramachandra\n* [[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]] as Captain Roland\n* [[Anthony Brandon Wong|Anthony Wong]] as Ghost\n* Henry Blasingame as Deus Ex Machina (motion capture)\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Deus Ex Machina (voice)\n* [[Tharini Mudaliar]] as Kamala\n* Maurice J. Morgan as a tower soldier\n}}\n\nActress [[Gloria Foster]], who played the Oracle in the first and second films, died before the completion of her filming for the third.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/05/theater/gloria-foster-stage-actress-is-dead-at-64.html|title=Gloria Foster, Stage Actress, Is Dead at 64|last=McKinley|first=Jesse|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 5, 2001|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref> She was replaced by actress [[Mary Alice]]. Her changed appearance is addressed in the film's plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-11-04/film/holy-trinity/full/|title=Holy Trinity|last=Hoberman|first=J.|authorlink=J. Hoberman|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=November 4, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Warner Bros Studios, Statues from Matrix.jpg|thumb|Warner Bros Studios, Statues from the Matrix]]\n[[Principal photography|Filming]] occurred concurrently with its predecessor, ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'', and live-action sequences for the [[video game]] ''[[Enter the Matrix]]''. This took place primarily at Fox Studios in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. Most notably, the subway scenes were filmed at the disused tunnels of [[St James railway station, Sydney|St James railway station]], and the end sequence with the Oracle and the Architect was filmed in the [[Royal Botanic Garden, Sydney|Royal Botanic Garden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/10/1052280481280.html|title=Sydney sci-fi fans rush to re-enter the Matrix|last=Sams|first=Christine|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=May 11, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-02-12/features/0302120056_1_wachowski-brothers-anthony-wong-matrix|title='Enter the Matrix' aims to open a new game era|last=Buchanan|first=Levi|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=February 12, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>  Carrie-Anne Moss broke her leg during the shooting in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Alana|title=Carrie Anne Moss: The Matrix Revolutions interview|date=November 3, 2003|publisher=[[BBC]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/11/03/carrie_anne_moss_the_matrix_revolutions_interview.shtml|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sound design===\nSound editing on ''The Matrix'' trilogy was completed by Danetracks in [[West Hollywood]], [[California]].\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{main|The Matrix Revolutions: Music from the Motion Picture}}\nIn contrast to its predecessors, very few \"source\" tracks are used in the film. Aside from [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]]' score, again collaborating with [[Juno Reactor]], only one external track (by [[Pale 3]]) is used. Although Davis rarely focuses on strong melodies, familiar [[leitmotif]]s from earlier in the series reappear. For example, Neo and Trinity's love theme\u2014which briefly surfaces in the two preceding films\u2014is finally fully expanded into \"Trinity Definitely\"; the theme from the Zion docks in ''Reloaded'' returns as \"Men in Metal\", and the energetic drumming from the ''Reloaded'' tea house fight between Neo and Seraph opens \"Tetsujin\", as Seraph, Trinity and Morpheus fight off Club Hel's three doormen. The climactic battle theme, named \"Neod\u00e4mmerung\" (in reference to [[Richard Wagner|Wagner]]'s ''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]''), features a choir singing extracts ([[shlokas]]) from the [[Pavamana Mantra]], introduced in the [[Upanishad]]s. The chorus can be roughly translated from [[Sanskrit]] as follows: \"lead us from untruth to truth, lead us from darkness to light, lead us from death to immortality, peace peace peace\". The extracts were brought to Davis by the Wachowskis when he informed them that it would be wasteful for such a large choir to be singing simple \"ooh\"s and \"aah\"s (according to the DVD commentary, Davis felt that the dramatic impact of the piece would be lost if the choir was to sing 'This is the one, see what he can do' in plain English). These extracts return in the film's denouement, and in ''Navras'', the track that plays over the closing credits (which may be considered a loose [[remix]] of \"Neod\u00e4mmerung\").\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film's budget was estimated between [[United States dollar|US$]]110 million<ref name=\"Allmovie (2010, The Matrix Revolutions)\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-matrix-revolutions-v282917|title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) \u2013 Andy Wachowski, Larry Wachowski \u2013 Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related \u2013 AllMovie|website=AllMovie|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425055503/http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-matrix-revolutions-282917 |archivedate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> and $150 million.<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> It grossed over $139 million in North America and approximately $427 million worldwide,<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> roughly half of ''The Matrix Reloaded'' box-office total. In its first five days of release, it grossed $83.8 million,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=matrixrevolutions.htm|title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) \u2013 Weekend Box Office Results |work= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> but dropped 66% during the second week.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Matrix Revolutions'' was released on DVD and VHS on April 6, 2004. The film grossed $116 million in DVD sales. Additionally, it was released on 4K Ultra HD Blu-Ray on October 30, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/62394/thematrixtrilogy4kultrahdbluray.html|title=The Matrix Trilogy - 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray Ultra HD Review {{!}} High Def Digest|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film received an approval rating of 35% based on 214 reviews, with an average rating of 5.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"A disappointing conclusion to the Matrix trilogy as characters and ideas take a back seat to the special effects.\"<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/matrix_revolutions/ |title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100 based on 41 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-matrix-revolutions |title=The Matrix Revolutions Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date=December 20, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSome critics criticized the film for being [[Anti-climax (narrative)|anticlimactic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slate.msn.com/id/2090753/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711065854/http://slate.msn.com/id/2090753 |archivedate=July 11, 2010 |title=Time to pull the plug on The Matrix. | author = David Edelstein | work = [[Slate Magazine]] |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=July 27, 2010 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clark |first=Mike |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2003-11-04-matrix-review_x.htm |title=\u2013 'The Matrix Revolutions': This big finish isn't The One |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=November 4, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Additionally, some critics regard the film as less philosophically ambiguous than its predecessor, ''The Matrix Reloaded''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott Foundas |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2003-11-13/film-tv/the-more-the-murkier/ |title=LA Weekly \u2013 Film+TV \u2013 The More the Murkier \u2013 Scott Foundas \u2013 The Essential Online Resource for Los Angeles |publisher=Laweekly.com |date=November 6, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/bal-to.matrix05nov05,0,2967920.story?coll=bal-artslife-movies |title=''Baltimore Sun'': 'The Matrix Revolutions' makes it a little easier to believe |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=May 6, 2004 |accessdate=July 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040506234616/http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/bal-to.matrix05nov05%2C0%2C2967920.story?coll=bal-artslife-movies |archivedate=May 6, 2004}}</ref> Critics had difficulty finding closure pertaining to events from ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'', and were generally dissatisfied.<ref>[http://ae.charlotte.com/entertainment/ui/charlotte/movie.html?id=99386&reviewId=13608&startDate=11%2F05%2F2003 'Matrix:' Neo-nonsense]{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9507E1D91F30F936A35752C1A9659C8B63 Movie Review|'The Matrix Revolutions': The Game Concludes With Light and Noise<!-- Bot generated title -->], archived at   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111162937/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9507E1D91F30F936A35752C1A9659C8B63 |date=November 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three stars out of four, despite offering criticisms of his own, on the grounds that it at least provided closure to the story well enough so that fans following the series would prefer seeing it as to not.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-matrix-revolutions-2003|title=The Matrix Revolutions Review | author=Roger Ebert | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=November 5, 2003 | accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Further|List of accolades received by The Matrix film series}}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main article|The Matrix 4}}\nWhile making the ''Matrix'' films, the Wachowskis told their close collaborators that at that time they had no intention of making another installment after ''The Matrix Revolutions''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/content/article/?id=107|title=Don Davis - Interview|work=soundtrack.net|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/11/1052591672027.html|title=Love bug bites the new Matrix - smh.com.au|work=smh.com.au|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2003/11/14/next-neo-thing/amp/|title=Next Neo Thing|date=November 14, 2003|work=ew.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyhaggis.com/2003/10/28/new-matrix-games-on-the-way/|title=New Matrix Games On The Way|date=October 28, 2003|publisher=}}</ref> Instead, they gave their blessing to the notion of [[gamers]] \"inherit[ing] the storyline\", and ''[[The Matrix Online]]'' video game was billed as the official continuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/04/11/the-matrix-online-2|title=The Matrix Online|first=Paul|last=Chadwick|date=April 11, 2005|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> In February 2015, in interviews promoting ''[[Jupiter Ascending]]'', Lilly Wachowski called a return to ''The Matrix'' a \"particularly repelling idea in these times\", noting the studios' tendency to green-light sequels, reboots, and adaptations over original material,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/wachowskis-unfazed-by-negativity-ahead-of-jupiter-ascending-launch-1.1751638|title=Wachowskis unfazed by negativity ahead of 'Jupiter Ascending' launch|first=Derrik J.|last=Lang|work=timescolonist.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> while Lana Wachowski, addressing rumors about a potential [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]], said that they had not heard anything, but she believed that the studio might be looking to replace them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/wachowskis-jupiter-ascending-interview/|title=The Wachowskis Talk JUPITER ASCENDING, Creating the Chicago Sequence, SENSE8, and More|date=February 4, 2015|work=collider.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> At various times, Keanu Reeves and Hugo Weaving have stated that they would be willing to reprise their roles in potential ''Matrix'' films, but only if the Wachowskis were involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/keanu-reeves-is-up-for-the-matrix-4-exclusive-135415356.html|title=Keanu Reeves is up for The Matrix 4 (exclusive)|work=yahoo.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/apr/18/hugo-weaving-on-revisiting-the-matrix-they-would-start-again-with-different-actors|title=Hugo Weaving on revisiting The Matrix: 'They would start again with different actors'|first=Luke|last=Buckmaster|date=April 17, 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that Warner Bros. was in early stages of developing a relaunch of the franchise, with [[Zak Penn]] in talks to write a treatment, and interest in getting [[Michael B. Jordan]] attached to star. According to the article neither the Wachowskis nor Joel Silver were involved at that stage, although the studio would like to get at minimum the blessing of the Wachowskis.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/matrix-reboot-works-at-warner-bros-986292|title='The Matrix' Reboot in the Works at Warner Bros. (Exclusive)|work=hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWarner Bros. officially announced the development on a fourth film in August 2019, with Lana Wachowski serving as director and producer on it. Lana will write the screenplay with [[David Mitchell (author)|David Mitchell]] and [[Aleksander Hemon]]. [[Grant Hill (producer)|Grant Hill]] will act as producer alongside Lana. The production will be a joint-venture between Warner Bros. Pictures and [[Village Roadshow Pictures]], similar to the original films. Keanu Reeves and Carrie-Anne Moss will reprise their roles from the previous films. Production began in February 2020 in [[San Francisco]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/matrix-4-keanu-reeves-carrie-anne-moss-lana-wachowski-1203307955/ | title = 'Matrix 4' Officially a Go With Keanu Reeves, Carrie-Anne Moss and Lana Wachowski  | first= Justin | last = Kroll | date = August 20, 2019 | accessdate = August 20, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/matrix-4-works-keanu-reeves-lana-wachowski-1233371 | title = 'Matrix 4' in the Works With Keanu Reeves and Lana Wachowski | first= Borys | last = Kit | date = August 20, 2019 | accessdate = August 20, 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref> and will also take place in [[Studio Babelsberg]] and [[Chicago]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring powered exoskeletons]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0242653}}\n* {{mojo title|matrixrevolutions}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|matrix_revolutions}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-matrix-revolutions}}\n* [http://wylfing.net/essays/matrix_revolutions.html ''The Matrix Revolutions'' Explained] \u2013 a comparative-literature-style exegesis of selected parts of ''Matrix Revolutions''.\n* {{cite web|url=http://dondavis.filmmusic.com/project_detail.html?id=matrix_revolutions |title=Lyrics to ''Neodammerung'', including translation |accessdate=September 20, 2004 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511052328/http://dondavis.filmmusic.com/project_detail.html?id=matrix_revolutions |archivedate=May 11, 2008}}\n* [http://thematrix101.com/revolutions/meaning.php Understanding ''The Matrix Revolutions''] \u2013 A comparative guide to possible meaning and interpretations of ''The Matrix Revolutions''\n* [http://www.horrorlair.com/movies/the_matrix_revolutions.html ''The Matrix Revolution'' October 27, 2000 draft script by Andy & Larry Wachowski]\n\n{{Matrix}}\n{{The Wachowskis}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Australia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matrix Revolutions, The}}\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2003 science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:The Matrix (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:American martial arts films]]\n[[Category:2003 martial arts films]]\n[[Category:2000s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk films]]\n[[Category:Drone films]]\n[[Category:Films about blind people]]\n[[Category:Films about rebellions]]\n[[Category:Films about telepresence]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Gun fu films]]\n[[Category:Kung fu films]]\n[[Category:Martial arts science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Powered exoskeletons in film]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Silver Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Village Roadshow Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Don Davis (composer)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by The Wachowskis]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joel Silver]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by The Wachowskis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name                 = The Matrix Revolutions\n| image                = Matrix revolutions ver7.jpg\n| caption              = Theatrical release poster\n| director             = [[The Wachowskis]]<!--Do not change without consensus. See [[Talk:The Matrix (franchise)#Request for Comment - Crediting The Wachowskis]]. -->{{efn|name=Credited|Credited as ''The Wachowski Brothers''.}}\n| producer             = [[Joel Silver]]\n| writer               = The Wachowskis\n| based on             = [[The Matrix (franchise)|Characters]]<br />by The Wachowskis\n| starring             = {{Plain list|\n* [[Keanu Reeves]]\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]]\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]]\n* [[Hugo Weaving]]\n* [[Jada Pinkett Smith]]\n}}\n| music                = [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]]\n| cinematography       = [[Bill Pope]]\n| editing              = [[Zach Staenberg]]\n| production companies = {{Plain list|\n* [[Village Roadshow Pictures]]\n* NPV Entertainment\n* [[Silver Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]\n| released             = {{Film date|2003|11|05|}}\n| runtime              = 129 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 128:48--><ref>{{cite web |title=The Matrix Revolutions |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/matrix-revolutions-2003 |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |accessdate=September 15, 2013}}</ref>\n| country              = United States<ref name=\"Lumiere\">{{cite web |title=''The Matrix Revolutions'' (2003) |url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=20284 |work=[[Lumiere (website)|Lumiere]] |accessdate=November 22, 2017 }}</ref><ref>http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/452404/Matrix-Revolutions-The/</ref>\n| language             = English\n| budget               = $110\u2013150 million<ref name=\"Allmovie (2010, The Matrix Revolutions)\" /><ref name=\"Mojo\" />\n| gross                = $427.3 million<ref name=\"Mojo\">{{cite web |title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=matrixrevolutions.htm |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Matrix Revolutions''''' is a 2003 American [[Science fiction film|science fiction]] [[action film]] written and directed by [[the Wachowskis]].{{efn|name=Credited}}<!--Do not change without consensus. See [[Talk:The Matrix (franchise)#Request for Comment - Crediting The Wachowskis]]. --> It was the third <!-- Please do not add \"and final\"; this is self-explanatory --> installment of [[The Matrix (franchise)|''The Matrix'' film franchise]], released six months following ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]''. The film was released simultaneously in 60 countries on November 5, 2003. While being the final entry in the original trilogy of the series, the ''Matrix'' storyline is continued in ''[[The Matrix Online]]''. It was the first live-action feature film to be released in both regular and [[IMAX]] theaters at the same time. Despite having a mixed reception from critics, the film grossed $427.3 million worldwide. A [[The Matrix 4|fourth ''Matrix'' film]] began production in February 2020.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- PER WP:FILM PLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES FOR FEATURE-LENGTH FILMS SHOULD BE BETWEEN 400 AND 700 WORDS.-->\n[[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]] and [[Bane (The Matrix)|Bane]] lie unconscious in the medical bay of the ship ''Hammer''. Inside the Matrix, Neo is trapped in a [[subway station]] named Mobil Ave (an anagram for [[limbo]]), a transition zone between the Matrix and the Machine City. He meets a \"family\" of programs, including a girl named Sati. The \"father\" tells Neo the subway is controlled by the Trainman, a program loyal to the [[Merovingian (The Matrix)|Merovingian]]. When Neo tries to board a train with the family, the Trainman refuses and overpowers him.\n\n[[Seraph (The Matrix)|Seraph]] contacts [[Morpheus (The Matrix)|Morpheus]] and [[Trinity (The Matrix)|Trinity]] on behalf of the [[Oracle (The Matrix)|Oracle]], who informs them of Neo's confinement. Seraph, Morpheus and Trinity enter [[Club Hel]], where they confront the Merovingian and force him to release Neo. Troubled by visions of the Machine City, Neo visits the Oracle, who reveals that [[Agent Smith|Smith]] intends to destroy both the Matrix and the real world. She states that \"everything that has a beginning has an end,\" and that the war will conclude. After Neo leaves, a large group of Smiths assimilates Sati and Seraph. One assimilates the Oracle and gains her powers of [[precognition]].\n\nIn the real world, the crews of the ''[[Nebuchadnezzar (The Matrix)|Nebuchadnezzar]]'' and the ''Hammer'' find and reactivate [[Niobe (The Matrix)|Niobe's]] ship, the ''Logos''. They interrogate Bane, who says that he has no recollection of the earlier massacre. As the captains plan their defense of Zion, Neo requests a ship to travel to the Machine City. Motivated by her [[Enter the Matrix|encounter with the Oracle]], Niobe offers him the ''Logos''. Neo departs, accompanied by Trinity. Bane, who has stowed away on the ''Logos'', takes Trinity hostage. Neo realizes that Bane has been assimilated by Smith and a fight ensues. Bane burns Neo's eyes with a power cable, permanently blinding him. Neo, discovering an ability to perceive anything part of the machine source code in the real world as wreathed in golden light, sees and kills Bane. Trinity pilots them to the Machine City.\n\nNiobe and Morpheus rush toward Zion in the ''Hammer'' to aid the human defenses. Zion's shipyard is overwhelmed by a horde of Sentinels, and the fatally wounded [[Captain Mifune]] instructs [[Kid (The Matrix)|Kid]] to open the gate for the ''Hammer''. When it arrives, it discharges its [[Electromagnetic pulse|EMP]], disabling all the Sentinels present but also Zion's remaining defenses. The humans are forced to retreat and wait for the next attack, thinking it will be their last stand.\n\nNear the Machine City, the ''Logos'' is bombarded by thousands of missiles, causing it to crash, fatally wounding Trinity. Neo enters the Machine City and encounters \"Deus Ex Machina,\" the machine leader. Neo warns that Smith plans to conquer both the Matrix and the real world and offers to stop Smith in exchange for peace with Zion. The machine leader agrees, and the Sentinels stop attacking Zion.\n\nThe Machines provide a connection for Neo to enter the Matrix. Inside, the Smith with the Oracle's powers steps forth, saying that he has foreseen his victory against Neo. After a protracted battle, Neo realizes there is no other way to win and allows himself to be assimilated. The machine leader sends a surge of energy into Neo's body in the real world. Because Neo is connected to the Source, the energy surge causes the Neo-Smith clone and all other Smith clones in the Matrix to be destroyed, deleting Smith once and for all. The Sentinels withdraw from Zion, Morpheus and Niobe embrace, and Neo sees a final vision of the machine city while seemingly succumbing to his injuries, as his body is carried away by the machines.\n\nThe Matrix is rebooted, and the Architect encounters the Oracle in a park. They agree that the peace will last \"as long as it can\" and that all humans will be offered the opportunity to leave the Matrix. When questioned about Neo's fate, the Oracle tells Sati that she thinks they will see Neo again as Sati reveals she created a beautiful sunrise over the horizon in Neo's honor. Seraph asks the Oracle if she knew this would happen. She replies that she did not know, but she believed.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Keanu Reeves]] as [[Neo (The Matrix)|Neo]]\n* [[Laurence Fishburne]] as [[Morpheus (The Matrix)|Morpheus]]\n* [[Carrie-Anne Moss]] as [[Trinity (The Matrix)|Trinity]]\n* [[Hugo Weaving]] as [[Agent Smith]]\n** [[Ian Bliss]] as Bane\n* [[Jada Pinkett Smith]] as [[Niobe (The Matrix)|Niobe]]\n* [[Mary Alice]] as [[The Oracle (The Matrix)|The Oracle]]\n* [[Harold Perrineau]] as Link\n* [[Monica Bellucci]] as [[Persephone (The Matrix)|Persephone]]\n* [[Harry J. Lennix]] as Commander Lock\n* [[Lambert Wilson]] as Merovingian\n* [[Nona Gaye]] as Zee\n* [[Anthony Zerbe]] as Councillor Hamann\n* [[Nathaniel Lees]] as Captain Mifune\n* [[Collin Chou]] as [[Seraph (The Matrix)|Seraph]]\n* [[Helmut Bakaitis]] as [[Architect (The Matrix)|The Architect]]\n* [[Tanveer K. Atwal]] as Sati\n* [[Bruce Spence]] as The Trainman\n* [[Gina Torres]] as Cas\n* [[Clayton Watson]] as Kid\n* [[Cornel West]] as Councillor West\n* [[Bernard White (actor)|Bernard White]] as Ramachandra\n* [[David Roberts (Australian actor)|David Roberts]] as Captain Roland\n* [[Anthony Brandon Wong|Anthony Wong]] as Ghost\n* Henry Blasingame as Deus Ex Machina (motion capture)\n* [[Kevin Michael Richardson]] as Deus Ex Machina (voice)\n* [[Tharini Mudaliar]] as Kamala\n* Maurice J. Morgan as a tower soldier\n}}\n\nActress [[Gloria Foster]], who played the Oracle in the first and second films, died before the completion of her filming for the third.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/05/theater/gloria-foster-stage-actress-is-dead-at-64.html|title=Gloria Foster, Stage Actress, Is Dead at 64|last=McKinley|first=Jesse|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 5, 2001|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref> She was replaced by actress [[Mary Alice]]. Her changed appearance is addressed in the film's plot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2003-11-04/film/holy-trinity/full/|title=Holy Trinity|last=Hoberman|first=J.|authorlink=J. Hoberman|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=November 4, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Warner Bros Studios, Statues from Matrix.jpg|thumb|Warner Bros Studios, Statues from the Matrix]]\n[[Principal photography|Filming]] occurred concurrently with its predecessor, ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'', and live-action sequences for the [[video game]] ''[[Enter the Matrix]]''. This took place primarily at Fox Studios in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]. Most notably, the subway scenes were filmed at the disused tunnels of [[St James railway station, Sydney|St James railway station]], and the end sequence with the Oracle and the Architect was filmed in the [[Royal Botanic Garden, Sydney|Royal Botanic Garden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/10/1052280481280.html|title=Sydney sci-fi fans rush to re-enter the Matrix|last=Sams|first=Christine|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|date=May 11, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2003-02-12/features/0302120056_1_wachowski-brothers-anthony-wong-matrix|title='Enter the Matrix' aims to open a new game era|last=Buchanan|first=Levi|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=February 12, 2003|accessdate=January 26, 2015}}</ref>  Carrie-Anne Moss broke her leg during the shooting in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Alana|title=Carrie Anne Moss: The Matrix Revolutions interview|date=November 3, 2003|publisher=[[BBC]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2003/11/03/carrie_anne_moss_the_matrix_revolutions_interview.shtml|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sound design===\nSound editing on ''The Matrix'' trilogy was completed by Danetracks in [[West Hollywood]], [[California]].\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{main|The Matrix Revolutions: Music from the Motion Picture}}\nIn contrast to its predecessors, very few \"source\" tracks are used in the film. Aside from [[Don Davis (composer)|Don Davis]]' score, again collaborating with [[Juno Reactor]], only one external track (by [[Pale 3]]) is used. Although Davis rarely focuses on strong melodies, familiar [[leitmotif]]s from earlier in the series reappear. For example, Neo and Trinity's love theme\u2014which briefly surfaces in the two preceding films\u2014is finally fully expanded into \"Trinity Definitely\"; the theme from the Zion docks in ''Reloaded'' returns as \"Men in Metal\", and the energetic drumming from the ''Reloaded'' tea house fight between Neo and Seraph opens \"Tetsujin\", as Seraph, Trinity and Morpheus fight off Club Hel's three doormen. The climactic battle theme, named \"Neod\u00e4mmerung\" (in reference to [[Richard Wagner|Wagner]]'s ''[[G\u00f6tterd\u00e4mmerung]]''), features a choir singing extracts ([[shlokas]]) from the [[Pavamana Mantra]], introduced in the [[Upanishad]]s. The chorus can be roughly translated from [[Sanskrit]] as follows: \"lead us from untruth to truth, lead us from darkness to light, lead us from death to immortality, peace peace peace\". The extracts were brought to Davis by the Wachowskis when he informed them that it would be wasteful for such a large choir to be singing simple \"ooh\"s and \"aah\"s (according to the DVD commentary, Davis felt that the dramatic impact of the piece would be lost if the choir was to sing 'This is the one, see what he can do' in plain English). These extracts return in the film's denouement, and in ''Navras'', the track that plays over the closing credits (which may be considered a loose [[remix]] of \"Neod\u00e4mmerung\").\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film's budget was estimated between [[United States dollar|US$]]110 million<ref name=\"Allmovie (2010, The Matrix Revolutions)\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/movie/the-matrix-revolutions-v282917|title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) \u2013 Andy Wachowski, Larry Wachowski \u2013 Synopsis, Characteristics, Moods, Themes and Related \u2013 AllMovie|website=AllMovie|accessdate=October 8, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100425055503/http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-matrix-revolutions-282917 |archivedate=April 25, 2010}}</ref> and $150 million.<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> It grossed over $139 million in North America and approximately $427 million worldwide,<ref name=\"Mojo\"/> roughly half of ''The Matrix Reloaded'' box-office total. In its first five days of release, it grossed $83.8 million,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=matrixrevolutions.htm|title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) \u2013 Weekend Box Office Results |work= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> but dropped 66% during the second week.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n===Home media===\n''The Matrix Revolutions'' was released on DVD and VHS on April 6, 2004. The film grossed $116 million in DVD sales. Additionally, it was released on 4K Ultra HD Blu-Ray on October 30, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/62394/thematrixtrilogy4kultrahdbluray.html|title=The Matrix Trilogy - 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray Ultra HD Review {{!}} High Def Digest|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=November 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film received an approval rating of 35% based on 214 reviews, with an average rating of 5.3/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"A disappointing conclusion to the Matrix trilogy as characters and ideas take a back seat to the special effects.\"<ref name=\"rt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/matrix_revolutions/ |title=The Matrix Revolutions (2003) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100 based on 41 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-matrix-revolutions |title=The Matrix Revolutions Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade B.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date=December 20, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSome critics criticized the film for being [[Anti-climax (narrative)|anticlimactic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slate.msn.com/id/2090753/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100711065854/http://slate.msn.com/id/2090753 |archivedate=July 11, 2010 |title=Time to pull the plug on The Matrix. | author = David Edelstein | work = [[Slate Magazine]] |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=July 27, 2010 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clark |first=Mike |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/reviews/2003-11-04-matrix-review_x.htm |title=\u2013 'The Matrix Revolutions': This big finish isn't The One |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=November 4, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref> Additionally, some critics regard the film as less philosophically ambiguous than its predecessor, ''The Matrix Reloaded''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott Foundas |url=http://www.laweekly.com/2003-11-13/film-tv/the-more-the-murkier/ |title=LA Weekly \u2013 Film+TV \u2013 The More the Murkier \u2013 Scott Foundas \u2013 The Essential Online Resource for Los Angeles |publisher=Laweekly.com |date=November 6, 2003 |accessdate=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/bal-to.matrix05nov05,0,2967920.story?coll=bal-artslife-movies |title=''Baltimore Sun'': 'The Matrix Revolutions' makes it a little easier to believe |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=May 6, 2004 |accessdate=July 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040506234616/http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/movies/bal-to.matrix05nov05%2C0%2C2967920.story?coll=bal-artslife-movies |archivedate=May 6, 2004}}</ref> Critics had difficulty finding closure pertaining to events from ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'', and were generally dissatisfied.<ref>[http://ae.charlotte.com/entertainment/ui/charlotte/movie.html?id=99386&reviewId=13608&startDate=11%2F05%2F2003 'Matrix:' Neo-nonsense]{{dead link|date=July 2012}}</ref><ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9507E1D91F30F936A35752C1A9659C8B63 Movie Review|'The Matrix Revolutions': The Game Concludes With Light and Noise<!-- Bot generated title -->], archived at   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121111162937/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9507E1D91F30F936A35752C1A9659C8B63 |date=November 11, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three stars out of four, despite offering criticisms of his own, on the grounds that it at least provided closure to the story well enough so that fans following the series would prefer seeing it as to not.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-matrix-revolutions-2003|title=The Matrix Revolutions Review | author=Roger Ebert | publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date=November 5, 2003 | accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Further|List of accolades received by The Matrix film series}}\n\n==Sequel==\n{{main article|The Matrix 4}}\nWhile making the ''Matrix'' films, the Wachowskis told their close collaborators that at that time they had no intention of making another installment after ''The Matrix Revolutions''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/content/article/?id=107|title=Don Davis - Interview|work=soundtrack.net|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/11/1052591672027.html|title=Love bug bites the new Matrix - smh.com.au|work=smh.com.au|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/article/2003/11/14/next-neo-thing/amp/|title=Next Neo Thing|date=November 14, 2003|work=ew.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyhaggis.com/2003/10/28/new-matrix-games-on-the-way/|title=New Matrix Games On The Way|date=October 28, 2003|publisher=}}</ref> Instead, they gave their blessing to the notion of [[gamers]] \"inherit[ing] the storyline\", and ''[[The Matrix Online]]'' video game was billed as the official continuation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/04/11/the-matrix-online-2|title=The Matrix Online|first=Paul|last=Chadwick|date=April 11, 2005|accessdate=October 8, 2017}}</ref> In February 2015, in interviews promoting ''[[Jupiter Ascending]]'', Lilly Wachowski called a return to ''The Matrix'' a \"particularly repelling idea in these times\", noting the studios' tendency to green-light sequels, reboots, and adaptations over original material,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/wachowskis-unfazed-by-negativity-ahead-of-jupiter-ascending-launch-1.1751638|title=Wachowskis unfazed by negativity ahead of 'Jupiter Ascending' launch|first=Derrik J.|last=Lang|work=timescolonist.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> while Lana Wachowski, addressing rumors about a potential [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]], said that they had not heard anything, but she believed that the studio might be looking to replace them.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/wachowskis-jupiter-ascending-interview/|title=The Wachowskis Talk JUPITER ASCENDING, Creating the Chicago Sequence, SENSE8, and More|date=February 4, 2015|work=collider.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> At various times, Keanu Reeves and Hugo Weaving have stated that they would be willing to reprise their roles in potential ''Matrix'' films, but only if the Wachowskis were involved.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/keanu-reeves-is-up-for-the-matrix-4-exclusive-135415356.html|title=Keanu Reeves is up for The Matrix 4 (exclusive)|work=yahoo.com|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/apr/18/hugo-weaving-on-revisiting-the-matrix-they-would-start-again-with-different-actors|title=Hugo Weaving on revisiting The Matrix: 'They would start again with different actors'|first=Luke|last=Buckmaster|date=April 17, 2017|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' wrote that Warner Bros. was in early stages of developing a relaunch of the franchise, with [[Zak Penn]] in talks to write a treatment, and interest in getting [[Michael B. Jordan]] attached to star. According to the article neither the Wachowskis nor Joel Silver were involved at that stage, although the studio would like to get at minimum the blessing of the Wachowskis.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/matrix-reboot-works-at-warner-bros-986292|title='The Matrix' Reboot in the Works at Warner Bros. (Exclusive)|work=hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWarner Bros. officially announced the development on a fourth film in August 2019, with Lana Wachowski serving as director and producer on it. Lana will write the screenplay with [[David Mitchell (author)|David Mitchell]] and [[Aleksander Hemon]]. [[Grant Hill (producer)|Grant Hill]] will act as producer alongside Lana. The production will be a joint-venture between Warner Bros. Pictures and [[Village Roadshow Pictures]], similar to the original films. Keanu Reeves and Carrie-Anne Moss will reprise their roles from the previous films. Production began in February 2020 in [[San Francisco]],<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/matrix-4-keanu-reeves-carrie-anne-moss-lana-wachowski-1203307955/ | title = 'Matrix 4' Officially a Go With Keanu Reeves, Carrie-Anne Moss and Lana Wachowski  | first= Justin | last = Kroll | date = August 20, 2019 | accessdate = August 20, 2019 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/matrix-4-works-keanu-reeves-lana-wachowski-1233371 | title = 'Matrix 4' in the Works With Keanu Reeves and Lana Wachowski | first= Borys | last = Kit | date = August 20, 2019 | accessdate = August 20, 2019 | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] }}</ref> and will also take place in [[Studio Babelsberg]] and [[Chicago]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of films featuring powered exoskeletons]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0242653}}\n* {{mojo title|matrixrevolutions}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|matrix_revolutions}}\n* {{metacritic film|the-matrix-revolutions}}\n* [http://wylfing.net/essays/matrix_revolutions.html ''The Matrix Revolutions'' Explained] \u2013 a comparative-literature-style exegesis of selected parts of ''Matrix Revolutions''.\n* {{cite web|url=http://dondavis.filmmusic.com/project_detail.html?id=matrix_revolutions |title=Lyrics to ''Neodammerung'', including translation |accessdate=September 20, 2004 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511052328/http://dondavis.filmmusic.com/project_detail.html?id=matrix_revolutions |archivedate=May 11, 2008}}\n* [http://thematrix101.com/revolutions/meaning.php Understanding ''The Matrix Revolutions''] \u2013 A comparative guide to possible meaning and interpretations of ''The Matrix Revolutions''\n* [http://www.horrorlair.com/movies/the_matrix_revolutions.html ''The Matrix Revolution'' October 27, 2000 draft script by Andy & Larry Wachowski]\n\n{{Matrix}}\n{{The Wachowskis}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Australia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matrix Revolutions, The}}\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:2003 science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:The Matrix (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:American martial arts films]]\n[[Category:2003 martial arts films]]\n[[Category:2000s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk films]]\n[[Category:Drone films]]\n[[Category:Films about blind people]]\n[[Category:Films about rebellions]]\n[[Category:Films about telepresence]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Sydney]]\n[[Category:Gun fu films]]\n[[Category:Kung fu films]]\n[[Category:Martial arts science fiction films]]\n[[Category:Powered exoskeletons in film]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n[[Category:Silver Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Village Roadshow Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Don Davis (composer)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by The Wachowskis]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Joel Silver]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by The Wachowskis]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:8583:fa15:709c:ab2f:92d3:29f5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Matrix_Revolutions"}
{"title_page": "Kurtis Gabriel", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian ice hockey player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Kurtis Gabriel\n| image = Kurtis Gabriel Iowa.jpg\n| caption =\n| image_size = \n| team = [[Philadelphia Flyers]]\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| prospect_team = [[Lehigh Valley Phantoms]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Minnesota Wild]]<br>[[New Jersey Devils]]\n| position = [[Winger (ice hockey)|Right Wing]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 200\n| shoots = Right\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|04|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Newmarket, Ontario]], Canada\n| draft = 81st overall\n| draft_year = 2013\n| draft_team = [[Minnesota Wild]]\n| career_start = 2014\n| career_end =\n}}\n'''Kurtis Gabriel''' (born April 20, 1993) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Forward (ice hockey)|forward]]. He is currently playing with the [[Lehigh Valley Phantoms]] in the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) while under contract with the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] of [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). \n\nAfter being passed over in the [[NHL Entry Draft]] during his first two years of eligibility, Gabriel was selected by the [[Minnesota Wild]] in the 3rd round (81st overall) of the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]]. He made his NHL debut with the Wild on November 10, 2015, but spent most of his tenure with their AHL affiliate, the [[Iowa Wild]]. He concluded his nearly five season tenure with the team following the [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318 season]], where he subsequently signed with the [[New Jersey Devils]]. Although Gabriel only spent one season with the Devils organization, he became the first NHL player to use Pride Tape outside of NHL designated [[You Can Play|Pride Nights]]. His advocacy work for the local community earned him the IOA/American Specialty AHL Man of the Year with the Wild and Phantoms.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGabriel was born on April 20, 1993,<ref name = \"Elite\">{{cite web |title=Kurtis Gabriel |url=https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/92683/kurtis-gabriel |website=eliteprospects.com |publisher=Elite Prospects |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> in [[Newmarket, Ontario]], Canada to mother Kim.<ref name = \"Smith\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Alex M. |title=Minnesota Wild prospect Kurtis Gabriel leans on his mom |url=https://www.twincities.com/2013/07/10/minnesota-wild-prospect-kurtis-gabriel-leans-on-his-mom/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |publisher=Twin Cities |date=July 10, 2013}}</ref> Growing up, he played hockey, baseball, basketball, volleyball, and ultimate frisbee.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McLoughlin |first1=Caela |title=Who the Devil is Kurtis Gabriel? |url=https://www.nhl.com/devils/news/who-the-devil-is-kurtis-gabriel/c-304792082 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> By the age of 10, Gabriel was playing Triple-A level hockey, until his father committed suicide and he dropped two divisions.<ref name = \"Smith\"/> He would later collaborate with the Shared Grief Project as a result of his father's suicide.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=NAGCNews|number=1128033362126483456|date=May 13, 2019|title=The Shared Grief Project has just released its newest video, featuring Kurtis Gabriel of the NHL's New Jersey Devils. Kurtis' father died from suicide when Kurtis was just 10.}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===Amateur===\nWhile attending [[Dr. John M. Denison Secondary School]], Gabriel was convinced by a friend to pursue hockey as a career. At that point, he had been splitting his time between baseball, soccer, and hockey and was considering pursuing a college basketball scholarship.<ref name = \"x\">{{cite web |title=Kurtis Gabriel: Living the Dream He Didn't Think Possible|last1= Witosky|first1=Tom|url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/354|website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=April 12, 2014}}</ref> He began playing for the AAA midgets [[Markham Waxers]] and York-Simcoe Express before earning an invite to the Jr. A Newmarket Hurricanes and Georgina Ice Jr. C evaluation camp.<ref name = \"Joyce\">{{cite web |last1=Joyce |first1=Gare |title=The Walk On \u2013 Kurtis Gabriel Story |url=https://attackhockey.com/the-walk-on-kurtis-gabriel-story |website=attackhockey.com |publisher=Owen Sound Attack|accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=March 31, 2013}}</ref> While participating in the Georgina Ice evaluation camp, he impressed the [[Ontario Hockey League]]'s (OHL) [[Owen Sound Attack]] scout Bryan Denney and was invited to their development camp.<ref>{{cite web |title=Long-shot Gabriel goes on Attack |url=https://www.yorkregion.com/community-story/1442764-long-shot-gabriel-goes-on-attack/ |website=yorkregion.com |publisher=York Region |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=September 23, 2010}}</ref> \n\nHe ended up playing four seasons in the OHL from 2010 to 2014, all with the Owen Sound Attack. Gabriel played in 40 games for Owen Sound during his rookie campaign and recorded four points.<ref name = \"hockeysfuture\">{{cite web |title=Kurtis Gabriel |url=https://www.hockeysfuture.com/prospects/kurtis-gabriel/ |website=hockeysfuture.com |publisher=Hockeys Future|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> After his first season in the OHL, Gabriel was not drafted at the [[2011 NHL Entry Draft]] but attended the [[Phoenix Coyotes]] Rookie Camp as a free agent invitee.<ref name = \"x\"/> Due to the [[2012\u201313 NHL lockout]], Gabriel was also not offered an invite to a rookie camp the following season, following a 17 point campaign.<ref name = \"Joyce\"/> When he returned to Owen Sound prior to the [[2012\u201313 OHL season|2012\u201313 season]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Main Camp Begins Today! |url=https://attackhockey.com/main-camp-begins-today |website=attackhockey.com |publisher=Owen Sound Attack |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=August 29, 2012}}</ref> he began his first breakout season. By December, he had earned the Attacker of the Week award for helping the team win in a shootout and later scoring the team's only goal in a 4\u20131 loss to the [[Plymouth Whalers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Gabriel Named Becker Shoes Attacker of the Week |url=https://attackhockey.com/gabriel-named-becker-shoes-attacker-of-the-week |website=attackhockey.com |publisher=Owen Sound Attack|accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Although Gabriel concluded the 2012\u201313 season with a career high 13 goals and 15 assists for 28 points, he was left off the [[NHL Central Scouting Bureau]]'s final ranking.<ref name = \"hockeysfuture\"/> In spite of being passed over in his first two years of eligibility, the [[Minnesota Wild]] eventually drafted him 81st overall in the [[2013 NHL Entry Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trio Goes for Attack on Draft Day |url=https://attackhockey.com/trio-goes-for-attack-on-draft-day |website=attackhockey.com |publisher=Owen Sound Attack|accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn his final session of major junior hockey, Gabriel was named an Assistant Captain<ref>{{cite web |title=Zach Nastasiuk named Attack captain |url=https://ontariohockeyleague.com/captain-nastasiuk/ |website=ontariohockeyleague.com |publisher=Ontario Hockey League |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=October 15, 2013}}</ref> and once again set a new career high in goals, assists, and points. On March 3, 2014, the Minnesota Wild signed Gabriel to a three-year entry-level contract.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wild Signs Gabriel To Entry Level Contract |url=https://www.nhl.com/wild/news/wild-signs-gabriel-to-entry-level-contract/c-707415 |website=NHL.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |date=March 18, 2014}}</ref> As the Owen Sound Attack qualified for the OHL playoffs, Gabriel was coming off a 10 game point streak.<ref>{{cite web |title=It\u2019s On |url=https://attackhockey.com/it-s-on |website=attackhockey.com |publisher=Owen Sound Attack |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=March 21, 2014}}</ref> During the first round of the OHL playoffs, Gabriel recorded one assist in an eventual loss to the [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kogut |first1=Megan |title=Wild Prospects Report - April 9 |url=https://www.nhl.com/wild/news/wild-prospects-report-april-9/c-713677 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422161314/https://www.nhl.com/wild/news/wild-prospects-report-april-9/c-713677 |archivedate=April 22, 2020 |date=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Professional===\nAfter the Owen Sound Attack were eliminated from the OHL playoffs, Gabriel was reassigned to the Minnesota Wild's [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Iowa Wild]].<ref name = \"x\"/> He recorded his first AHL goal on April 16, 2014, in a 4\u20133 shootout loss to the [[Chicago Wolves]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Wolves Defeat Wild 4\u20133 in a Shootout|url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/362 |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=April 16, 2014}}</ref> and ended the season with four points in eight games.<ref name = \"Elite\"/>\n\nFollowing a successful eight games in the 2013\u201314 season, Gabriel was invited to participate at the Minnesota Wild's Training Camp prior to the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wild Training Camp Roster Set At 56 |url=https://www.nhl.com/wild/news/wild-training-camp-roster-set-at-56/c-730820 |website=nhl.com/ |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=September 17, 2014}}</ref> He eventually began his first full professional season with the Iowa Wild, where he recorded seven goals and 16 points overall in 67 games.<ref>{{cite web |title=AFTER FURTHER REVIEW: KURTIS GABRIEL |url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/1142 |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=June 2, 2016}}</ref> This gained attention from the National Hockey League and he was invited to participate in the Minnesota Wild's September training camp prior to the 2015\u201316 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=24 Iowa Wild Players On Minnesota's Training Camp Roster|url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/804 |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=September 16, 2015}}</ref> Although he was unbale to crack the Wild's lineup to begin the season,<ref>{{cite web |title=Iowa Wild Announced Training Camp Roster|url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/823 |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=September 29, 2015}}</ref> Gabriel made his NHL debut on November 10, 2015, in a game against the [[Winnipeg Jets]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Gabriel sees his NHL dreams come true |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/juniors/gabriel-sees-his-nhl-dreams-come-true/ |website=sportsnet.ca |publisher=Sportsnet|accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=November 11, 2015}}</ref> before being reassigned the following day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Ryan |title=Wild assign forward Gabriel to AHL\u2019s Iowa |url=https://www.foxsports.com/north/story/minnesota-wild-kurtis-gabriel-to-ahl-iowa-111115 |website=foxsports.com |publisher=Fox Sports |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=November 11, 2015}}</ref> At the end of the regular season, the Iowa Wild named him their IOA/American Specialty AHL Man of the Year for his \"outstanding contributions to the Des Moines community during the 2015\u201316 season.\"<ref name = \"MOY1\">{{cite web |title=Kurtis Gabriel Named Iowas 2015-16 IOA/American Speciality AHL Man Of The Year |url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/1096 |website=iowawild.com|publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> As the Iowa Wild failed to qualify for the [[2016 Calder Cup playoffs]], he made his first [[Stanley Cup playoffs]] appearance with the Minnesota Wild against the [[Dallas Stars]] on April 18.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Russo |first1=Michael |title=Iowa call-up Kurtis Gabriel thrilled about being in playoffs with Wild |url=http://www.startribune.com/iowa-call-up-kurtis-gabriel-thrilled-about-being-in-playoffs-with-wild/376299831/ |accessdate=November 20, 2018 |publisher=Star Tribune |date=April 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGabriel spent the majority of the [[2016\u201317 AHL season|2016\u201317]] season with the Iowa Wild, only playing 13 games in the NHL. On February 27, 2017, Gabriel was suspended for six AHL games as the result of off ice actions taken place two days prior.<ref>{{cite web |title=AHL announces suspension |url=https://theahl.com/ahl-announces-suspension-17feb27 |website=theahl.com |publisher=American Hockey League |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |date=February 27, 2017}}</ref> Despite this, Gabriel ended the season with 10 points in 40 games for the Wild and accrued 68 penalty minutes. He signed a one year contract with the Minnesota Wild on July 10, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wild Re-Signs Kurtis Gabriel for One Year |url=https://www.nhl.com/wild/news/gabriel-re-signed-071017/c-290342014 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120095935/http://www.nhl.com/wild/news/gabriel-re-signed-071017/c-290342014 |archivedate=November 20, 2018 |date=July 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2017\u201318 AHL season|2017\u201318 season]], Gabriel endured a partial cut to his median nerve and damage to a major muscle and a ligament in his wrist as the result of accidentally falling on a skate blade. He underwent surgery three days after the game and was expected to return to the lineup before the season concluded.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Witosky |first1=Tom |title=KURTIS GABRIEL ON THE ROAD TO RECOVERY |url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/kurtis-gabriel-on-the-road-to-recovery |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=December 1, 2017}}</ref> He eventually returned to the Wild's lineup in February 2018, for their games against Chicago and Rockford.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Witosky |first1=Tom |title=Gabriel's Return: Expected To Play Big Role in Iowa's Playoff Race|url=https://www.iowawild.com/news/detail/gabriels-return-expected-to-play-big-role-in-iowas-playoff-hunt |website=iowawild.com |publisher=Iowa Wild |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Upon returning, he spent the entirety of the season in the AHL and was unable earn a recall to Minnesota through the 2017\u201318 season. As a result, Gabriel left the Wild organization as a free agent during the offseason and signed a one-year, two-way contract with the [[New Jersey Devils]] on July 2, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Devils sign forward Kurtis Gabriel to one-year, two-way contract |url=https://www.nhl.com/devils/news/devils-sign-forward-kurtis-gabriel-to-one-year-two-way-contract/c-299383802 |website=nhl.com |publisher=National Hockey League |accessdate=April 23, 2020 |archiveurl=https://www.nhl.com/devils/news/devils-sign-forward-kurtis-gabriel-to-one-year-two-way-contract/c-299383802 |archivedate=July 2, 2018 |date=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n[[File: Kurtis Gabriel\u2019s Pride sticks.jpg|thumb|A photo of Gabriel's stick with pride tape on it during the 2018\u201319 season]]\nFollowing training camp, Gabriel was assigned to the Devils AHL affiliate, the [[Binghamton Devils]], to begin the [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ryan |first1=Chris |title=Devils make 1st significant cuts of training camp |url=https://www.nj.com/devils/2018/09/devils_make_1st_significant_cuts_of_training_camp.html |website=NJ.com |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=September 23, 2018}}</ref> After earning a recall to the NHL, he became the first NHL player to play a game while using Pride Tape<ref>{{cite web |last1=Douglas |first1=William |title=Gabriel scores big win for inclusion with use of Pride Tape in NHL game |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/kurtis-gabriel-was-first-nhl-player-to-use-pride-tape-in-game/c-307671020 |website=NHL.com|publisher=National Hockey League|accessdate=April 21, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130155117/https://www.nhl.com/news/kurtis-gabriel-was-first-nhl-player-to-use-pride-tape-in-game/c-307671020 |date=June 3, 2019|archive-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref> and continue to use it past Pride Night.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ianniello |first1=Mike |title=Kurtis Gabriel Takes Pride in Making a Difference |url=http://www.phantomshockey.com/kurtis-gabriel-takes-pride-making-difference/ |website=phantomshockey.com |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> On February 21, 2019, he scored his first NHL goal with the Devils against the [[Ottawa Senators]], in a 4\u20130 win.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cudmore |first1=John |title=Newmarket's Gabriel scores 1 for mom in New Jersey Devils' win |url=https://www.wellandtribune.ca/community-story/9189258-newmarket-s-gabriel-scores-1-for-mom-in-new-jersey-devils-win/ |accessdate=April 21, 2020 |publisher=Welland Tribune |date=February 22, 2019}}</ref> He later received a one game suspension for boarding [[Philadelphia Flyers]] player [[Nolan Patrick]] during a game; it was a short suspension as a result of it being his first time offence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hall |first1=Jordan |title=Devils' Kurtis Gabriel receives 1-game suspension from NHL for boarding Nolan Patrick |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/flyers/devils-kurtis-gabriel-receives-1-game-suspension-nhl-boarding-nolan-patrick |website=nbcsports.com |publisher=NBC Sports |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> During the game, Gabriel was only assessed a five-minute boarding major penalty and Patrick later elbowed him in the head causing him to leave the ice.<ref>{{cite web |title=Devils\u2019 Kurtis Gabriel to have hearing for boarding Flyers\u2019 Nolan Patrick |url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/hockey/nhl/devils-kurtis-gabriel-hearing-boarding-flyers-nolan-patrick/ |website=sportsnet.ca |publisher=Sportsnet |accessdate=April 24, 2020 |date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> Gabriel concluded his only season with the New Jersey Devils recording four points in 22 games. On July 1, 2019, Gabriel left the Devils as a free agent to sign a one-year, two-way contract with the Philadelphia Flyers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flyers ink Andreoff, Gabriel, Prosser |url=https://theahl.com/flyers-ink-andreoff-gabriel-prosser |website=theahl.com |publisher=American Hockey League |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the Flyers 2019 Training camp, Gabriel was assigned to their American Hockey League affiliate, the [[Lehigh Valley Phantoms]], to begin the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flyers Assign More Players to Phantoms as Training Camp Continues |url=http://www.phantomshockey.com/flyers-assign-players-phantoms-training-camp-continues/ |website=phantomshockey.com |publisher=Lehigh Valley Phantoms |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> During his first season with the Flyers organization, Gabriel continued to be the only player in the AHL to use pride tape during every game beyond Pride Night. He also became the Phantoms [[You Can Play]] project ambassador and was part of a feature story on [[WFMZ-TV]] about inclusion in hockey. As a result, he was named the Phantoms 2020 IOA/American Specialty AHL Man of the Year.<ref name = \"MOY2\">{{cite web |title=Kurtis Gabriel Named Lehigh Valley\u2019s 2019-20 IOA/American Specialty AHL Man Of The Year |url=http://www.phantomshockey.com/kurtis-gabriel-named-lehigh-valleys-2019-20-ioaamerican-specialty-ahl-man-year/ |website=phantomshockey.com |publisher=Lehigh Valley Phantoms |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\nGabriel has been described as an [[Enforcer (ice hockey)|enforcer]] but has shown the ability to score points when needed.<ref name = \"Mastracco\"/> One of the main critiques of his game growing up was his lack of skating ability.<ref name = \"x\"/>\n\nWhen the New Jersey Devils signed Gabriel to a one year contract, coach John Hynes spoke highly of Gabriel as a player:\n{{Quote\n|text=He\u2019s a guy who brings attributes that a lot of other players don\u2019t...He brings toughness, he brings physicality, he\u2019s got good hands, he\u2019s defensively responsible, he can finish and when he finishes he hits through people. He\u2019s definitely a presence.<ref name = \"Mastracco\">{{cite news |last1=Mastracco |first1=Abbey |title=Why NJ Devils think Kurtis Gabriel can be more than just an enforcer |url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/sports/nhl/devils/2019/02/18/why-nj-devils-think-kurtis-gabriel-can-more-than-just-enforcer/2902784002/ |accessdate=April 22, 2020 |publisher=USA Today |date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"  bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! rowspan=\"101\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! colspan=\"5\"                    | [[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"101\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! colspan=\"5\"                    | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2010\u201311 OHL season|2010\u201311]]\n| [[Owen Sound Attack]]\n| [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]\n| 40\n| 1\n| 3\n| 4\n| 20\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2011\u201312 OHL season|2011\u201312]]\n| Owen Sound Attack\n| OHL\n| 65\n| 4\n| 13\n| 17\n| 72\n| 4\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2012\u201313 OHL season|2012\u201313]]\n| Owen Sound Attack\n| OHL\n| 67\n| 13\n| 15\n| 28\n| 100\n| 12\n| 3\n| 2\n| 5\n| 34\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"